{"title_page": "Brandon Bostick", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n| name          = Brandon Bostick\n| image         = Brandon Bostick 2016.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Bostick with the [[New York Jets|Jets]] in [[2016 New York Jets season|2016]]\n| number        = --\n| position      = [[Tight end]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1989|5|3}}\n| birth_place   = [[Florence, South Carolina]]\n| height_ft     = 6\n| height_in     = 3\n| weight_lbs    = 250\n| high_school   = [[West Florence High School|Florence (SC) West]]\n| college       = [[Newberry Wolves football|Newberry]]\n| undraftedyear = 2012\n| pastteams     =\n* [[Green Bay Packers]] ({{NFL Year|2012}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2014}})\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ({{NFL Year|2015}})*\n* [[Arizona Cardinals]] ({{NFL Year|2015}})*\n* [[New York Jets]] ({{NFL Year|2015}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2016}})\n| pastteamsnote = yes\n| status        =\n| highlights    =\n| statleague    = NFL\n| statweek      = \n| statseason    = 2016\n| statlabel3    = Receptions\n| statvalue3    = 17\n| statlabel4    = Receiving yards\n| statvalue4    = 186\n| statlabel5    = Receiving touchdowns\n| statvalue5    = 2\n| nflnew        = brandonbostick/2536342\n}}\n\n'''Brandon Jamal Bostick''' (born May 3, 1989) is a former [[American football]] [[tight end]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Newberry Wolves football|Newberry]]. Bostick was signed by the [[Green Bay Packers]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 2012. During the 2014 playoffs, he costed the packers a trip to the super bowl by dropping the ball from an onside kick against the Seahawks. This costed the Packers a trip to the super bowl and probably one of the most exciting Super Bowl match ups between Aaron Rodgers and the Packers vs Tom Brady and the patriots. He has also been a member of the [[Minnesota Vikings]], [[Arizona Cardinals]] and [[New York Jets]].\n\n==Early life and college career==\nBostick was born in [[Florence, South Carolina]] and graduated from [[West Florence High School]] in 2007. He then attended [[Newberry College]], a [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] school. After redshirting his freshman year, Bostick played at Newberry as [[wide receiver]] from the 2008 to 2011 seasons. In 39 games, he started 24 and made 136 receptions for 1,935 yards and 19 touchdowns. Bostick also played basketball at Newberry for the second half of his junior season.<ref name=\"Packers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.packers.com/team/roster/Brandon-Bostick/855d5326-2230-4a0b-9f22-20b58a40a56b|title=Brandon Bostick|publisher=Green Bay Packers|accessdate=January 19, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Newberry\">{{cite web|title=Brandon Bostick|url=http://newberryathleticsite.com/profile.asp?playerID=1228|publisher=Newberry College|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111118202415/http://newberryathleticsite.com/profile.asp?playerID=1228|archivedate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> He was a [[sports management]] major at Newberry.<ref name=\"Newberry\"/>\n\n==Professional career==\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 3\n|       weight = 243\n|         dash = 4.59\n|    ten split = 1.67\n| twenty split = 2.73\n|      shuttle = 4.25\n|   cone drill = 7.41\n|     vertical = 36\n|     broad ft = 10\n|     broad in = 1\n|        bench = 19\n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = \n|    hand span = \n|         note = All values are from [[Pro Day]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=104009&draftyear=2012&genpos=fb|title=Brandon Bostick - Newberry, FB : 2012 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile|work=NFLDraftScout.com|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Green Bay Packers===\n[[File:Brandon Bostick in 2014.jpg|thumb|Bostick at Packers training camp in 2014.]]\nHe was signed by the Packers as an [[undrafted free agent]] on May 30, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brandon Bostick signs contract with Green Bay Packers|url=http://www.newberrywolves.com/fb/news/2011-12/5278/brandon-bostick-signs-contract-with-green-bay-packers/|publisher=Newberry College|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=May 30, 2012}}</ref> Bostick spent his entire rookie season in 2012 on the practice squad.<ref name=\"Packers\"/>\n\nPlaying primarily on special teams, Bostick made his NFL debut on September 15, 2013 against [[2013 Washington Redskins season|Washington]].<ref name=\"Packers detailed\">{{citation|title=Brandon Bostick|url=http://prod.static.packers.clubs.nfl.com/assets/docs/2014/2014-packers-83-268.pdf|website=Packers 2014 Media Guide|publisher=Green Bay Packers|pages=92\u201393|date=2014}}</ref> He recorded his first NFL touchdown catch on November 10, 2013 against the [[2013 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], on a 22-yard pass from [[Scott Tolzien]], in a play that was also Tolzien's first career touchdown pass.<ref name=\"Packers\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Reischel|first1=Rob|title=Scott Tolzien shifts from practice squad to starter|url=http://www.jsonline.com/sports/packers/scott-tolzien-shifts-from-practice-squad-to-starter-b99139504z1-231682991.html|website=Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=November 12, 2013}}</ref> Bostick finished the 2013 season with 7 receptions for 120 yards and a touchdown in 11 games.<ref name=\"Packers\"/> He missed the [[NFL on Thanksgiving Day|Thanksgiving Classic]] due to a concussion suffered during the November 24 game.  On December 15 against [[2013 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas]], Bostick suffered a foot injury late in the second half; he was placed on season-ending injured reserve six days later.<ref name=\"Packers detailed\"/>\n\nBostick played 13 games in the 2014 season and made 2 receptions for 3 yards and a touchdown.<ref name=\"Packers\"/> On November 9, in a [[NBC Sunday Night Football|Sunday night]] 55-14 win over the [[2014 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]], Bostick made the Packers' first touchdown score, on a pass from [[Aaron Rodgers]] on fourth down from the Bears' 1-yard line.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gamecenter: Chicago Bears at Green Bay Packers|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2014110910/2014/REG10/bears@packers#menu=gameinfo&#124;contentId%3A0ap3000000425849&tab=analyze|publisher=NFL|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=November 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs#NFC Championship Game: Seattle Seahawks 28.2C Green Bay Packers 22 .28OT.29|NFC Championship Game]] against the [[2014 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] on January 18, 2015, with slightly over 2 minutes remaining and the Packers leading 19\u201314, Bostick, the Packers' third-string tight end, misplayed a Seahawks [[onside kick]]. The ball bounced off his helmet and was recovered by Seahawks wide receiver [[Chris Matthews (American football)|Chris Matthews]]. In the ensuing drive, the Seahawks scored a touchdown and two-point conversion to go ahead 22\u201319. [[Mason Crosby]] made a game-tying field goal with 14 seconds left, but Seattle won 28\u201322 in overtime.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wilner|first1=Barry|title=Seahawks rally stuns Packers 28\u201322 in OT for NFC title|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/seahawks-rally-stuns-packers-28-22-ot-nfc-title|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=January 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Divish|first1=Ryan|title=Seahawks\u2019 miracle rally tops Packers, earns Super Bowl trip|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/seahawks/2025494755_seahawksonlinegamer19xml.html|website=Seattle Times|accessdate=January 18, 2015}}</ref> In his postgame interview, Bostick acknowledged that he was supposed to block so that [[Jordy Nelson]] could recover the onside kick.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wood |first1=Ryan |title=Bostick admits play for onside kick 'not my job' |url=http://www.greenbaypressgazette.com/story/sports/nfl/packers/2015/01/18/bostick-admits-play-for-onside-kick-not-my-job/21976159/ |website=Green Bay Press-Gazette |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ViShFXk9?url=http://www.greenbaypressgazette.com/story/sports/nfl/packers/2015/01/18/bostick-admits-play-for-onside-kick-not-my-job/21976159/ |archivedate=January 20, 2015 |date=January 19, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Bostick was released on February 16, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fantasynews.cbssports.com/fantasyfootball/update/25070773/packers-release-nfc-title-game-goat-brandon-bostick|title=Packers release NFC title game goat Brandon Bostick|last=Krest|first=Shawn|work=fantasynews.cbssports.com|date=February 16, 2015|accessdate=February 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Minnesota Vikings===\nBostick was claimed off waivers by the [[Minnesota Vikings]] on February 18, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000471264/article/vikings-claim-brandon-bostick-off-waivers|title=Vikings claim tight end Brandon Bostick off waivers|first=Nick|last=Shook|work=NFL.com|date=February 18, 2015|accessdate=February 18, 2015}}</ref> Bostick was released by the Vikings as part of the first wave of roster cuts on August 30, 2015.\n\n===Arizona Cardinals===\nOn September 7, 2015, the [[Arizona Cardinals]] signed Bostick to their practice squad.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301044621/http://www.azcardinals.com/news-and-events/article-2/Practice-Squad-Set-For-Cardinals/0e6435c2-45b2-4b05-aea5-e7234141db91 |title=Practice Squad Set For Cardinals |last=Urban |first=Darren |date=September 7, 2015 |website=AZCardinals.com |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> On September 22, 2015, he was released by the Cardinals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.azcardinals.com/2015/09/22/kerwynn-williams-cut-as-massie-returns/ |title=Kerwynn Williams cut as Massie returns |last=Urban |first=Darren |date=September 22, 2015 |website=AZCardinals.com |accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref> On October 2, 2015, Bostick was re-signed to the Cardinals' practice squad.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.azcardinals.com/news-and-events/article-2/Looking-To-Break-Out-Michael-Floyd/f12622a4-3959-425b-b9b4-c9d2eb3cade3 |title=Looking To Break Out Michael Floyd |last=Urban |first=Darren |date=October 2, 2015 |website=AZCardinals.com |accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref> On December 1, 2015, he was released from practice squad.\n\n===New York Jets===\nOn December 8, 2015, the [[New York Jets]] signed Bostick to their practice squad.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lange|first1=Randy|title=Jets Place DE Mike Catapano (Foot) on IR|url=http://www.newyorkjets.com/news/article-9/Jets-Place-DE-Mike-Catapano-Foot-on-IR/d93d4a78-b869-4698-9073-72ef3161a0f3|website=NewYorkJets.com|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n''Source: [http://www.nfl.com/player/brandonbostick/2536342/profile NFL.com]''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|G !! rowspan=\"2\"|GS !! colspan=\"5\"|Receiving !! colspan=\"2\"|Fumbles\n|-\n! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Fum !! Lost\n|-\n! colspan=11|'''Regular season'''\n|-\n! [[2013 NFL season|2013]] !! [[2013 Green Bay Packers season|GB]]\n| 11 || 0 || 7 || 120 || 17.1 || 26 || 1 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2014 NFL season|2014]] !! [[2014 Green Bay Packers season|GB]]\n| 13 || 0 || 2 || 3 || 1.5 || 2 || 1 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] !! [[2016 New York Jets season|NYJ]]\n| 16 || 7 || 8 || 63 || 7.9 || 14 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total || 40 || 7 || 17 || 186 || 10.9 || 26 || 2 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=11|'''Postseason'''\n|-\n! [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs|2014]] !! [[2014 Green Bay Packers season|GB]]\n| 2 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total || 2 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nHis cousin, [[Akeem Bostick]], plays in [[Minor League Baseball]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rangersblog.dallasnews.com/2013/06/meet-the-rangers-third-draft-pick-rhp-akeem-bostic.html/|title=Meet the Rangers\u2019 third draft pick: RHP Akeem Bostic|work=Texas Rangers Blog|accessdate=January 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.packers.com/team/roster/brandon-bostick/855d5326-2230-4a0b-9f22-20b58a40a56b Green Bay Packers bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bostick, Brandon}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Florence, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:American football tight ends]]\n[[Category:Newberry Wolves football players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings players]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:New York Jets players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL player\n| name          = Brandon Bostick\n| image         = Brandon Bostick 2016.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = Bostick with the [[New York Jets|Jets]] in [[2016 New York Jets season|2016]]\n| number        = --\n| position      = [[Tight end]]\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1989|5|3}}\n| birth_place   = [[Florence, South Carolina]]\n| height_ft     = 6\n| height_in     = 3\n| weight_lbs    = 250\n| high_school   = [[West Florence High School|Florence (SC) West]]\n| college       = [[Newberry Wolves football|Newberry]]\n| undraftedyear = 2012\n| pastteams     =\n* [[Green Bay Packers]] ({{NFL Year|2012}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2014}})\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ({{NFL Year|2015}})*\n* [[Arizona Cardinals]] ({{NFL Year|2015}})*\n* [[New York Jets]] ({{NFL Year|2015}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2016}})\n| pastteamsnote = yes\n| status        =\n| highlights    =\n| statleague    = NFL\n| statweek      = \n| statseason    = 2016\n| statlabel3    = Receptions\n| statvalue3    = 17\n| statlabel4    = Receiving yards\n| statvalue4    = 186\n| statlabel5    = Receiving touchdowns\n| statvalue5    = 2\n| nflnew        = brandonbostick/2536342\n}}\n\n'''Brandon Jamal Bostick''' (born May 3, 1989) is a former [[American football]] [[tight end]]. He played [[college football]] at [[Newberry Wolves football|Newberry]]. Bostick was signed by the [[Green Bay Packers]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 2012. He has also been a member of the [[Minnesota Vikings]], [[Arizona Cardinals]] and [[New York Jets]].\n\n==Early life and college career==\nBostick was born in [[Florence, South Carolina]] and graduated from [[West Florence High School]] in 2007. He then attended [[Newberry College]], a [[NCAA Division II|Division II]] school. After redshirting his freshman year, Bostick played at Newberry as [[wide receiver]] from the 2008 to 2011 seasons. In 39 games, he started 24 and made 136 receptions for 1,935 yards and 19 touchdowns. Bostick also played basketball at Newberry for the second half of his junior season.<ref name=\"Packers\">{{cite web|url=http://www.packers.com/team/roster/Brandon-Bostick/855d5326-2230-4a0b-9f22-20b58a40a56b|title=Brandon Bostick|publisher=Green Bay Packers|accessdate=January 19, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Newberry\">{{cite web|title=Brandon Bostick|url=http://newberryathleticsite.com/profile.asp?playerID=1228|publisher=Newberry College|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111118202415/http://newberryathleticsite.com/profile.asp?playerID=1228|archivedate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> He was a [[sports management]] major at Newberry.<ref name=\"Newberry\"/>\n\n==Professional career==\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 3\n|       weight = 243\n|         dash = 4.59\n|    ten split = 1.67\n| twenty split = 2.73\n|      shuttle = 4.25\n|   cone drill = 7.41\n|     vertical = 36\n|     broad ft = 10\n|     broad in = 1\n|        bench = 19\n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = \n|    hand span = \n|         note = All values are from [[Pro Day]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfldraftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=104009&draftyear=2012&genpos=fb|title=Brandon Bostick - Newberry, FB : 2012 NFL Draft Scout Player Profile|work=NFLDraftScout.com|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===Green Bay Packers===\n[[File:Brandon Bostick in 2014.jpg|thumb|Bostick at Packers training camp in 2014.]]\nHe was signed by the Packers as an [[undrafted free agent]] on May 30, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Brandon Bostick signs contract with Green Bay Packers|url=http://www.newberrywolves.com/fb/news/2011-12/5278/brandon-bostick-signs-contract-with-green-bay-packers/|publisher=Newberry College|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=May 30, 2012}}</ref> Bostick spent his entire rookie season in 2012 on the practice squad.<ref name=\"Packers\"/>\n\nPlaying primarily on special teams, Bostick made his NFL debut on September 15, 2013 against [[2013 Washington Redskins season|Washington]].<ref name=\"Packers detailed\">{{citation|title=Brandon Bostick|url=http://prod.static.packers.clubs.nfl.com/assets/docs/2014/2014-packers-83-268.pdf|website=Packers 2014 Media Guide|publisher=Green Bay Packers|pages=92\u201393|date=2014}}</ref> He recorded his first NFL touchdown catch on November 10, 2013 against the [[2013 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], on a 22-yard pass from [[Scott Tolzien]], in a play that was also Tolzien's first career touchdown pass.<ref name=\"Packers\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Reischel|first1=Rob|title=Scott Tolzien shifts from practice squad to starter|url=http://www.jsonline.com/sports/packers/scott-tolzien-shifts-from-practice-squad-to-starter-b99139504z1-231682991.html|website=Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=November 12, 2013}}</ref> Bostick finished the 2013 season with 7 receptions for 120 yards and a touchdown in 11 games.<ref name=\"Packers\"/> He missed the [[NFL on Thanksgiving Day|Thanksgiving Classic]] due to a concussion suffered during the November 24 game.  On December 15 against [[2013 Dallas Cowboys season|Dallas]], Bostick suffered a foot injury late in the second half; he was placed on season-ending injured reserve six days later.<ref name=\"Packers detailed\"/>\n\nBostick played 13 games in the 2014 season and made 2 receptions for 3 yards and a touchdown.<ref name=\"Packers\"/> On November 9, in a [[NBC Sunday Night Football|Sunday night]] 55-14 win over the [[2014 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]], Bostick made the Packers' first touchdown score, on a pass from [[Aaron Rodgers]] on fourth down from the Bears' 1-yard line.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gamecenter: Chicago Bears at Green Bay Packers|url=http://www.nfl.com/gamecenter/2014110910/2014/REG10/bears@packers#menu=gameinfo&#124;contentId%3A0ap3000000425849&tab=analyze|publisher=NFL|accessdate=January 20, 2015|date=November 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs#NFC Championship Game: Seattle Seahawks 28.2C Green Bay Packers 22 .28OT.29|NFC Championship Game]] against the [[2014 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] on January 18, 2015, with slightly over 2 minutes remaining and the Packers leading 19\u201314, Bostick, the Packers' third-string tight end, misplayed a Seahawks [[onside kick]]. The ball bounced off his helmet and was recovered by Seahawks wide receiver [[Chris Matthews (American football)|Chris Matthews]]. In the ensuing drive, the Seahawks scored a touchdown and two-point conversion to go ahead 22\u201319. [[Mason Crosby]] made a game-tying field goal with 14 seconds left, but Seattle won 28\u201322 in overtime.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wilner|first1=Barry|title=Seahawks rally stuns Packers 28\u201322 in OT for NFC title|url=http://pro32.ap.org/article/seahawks-rally-stuns-packers-28-22-ot-nfc-title|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=January 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Divish|first1=Ryan|title=Seahawks\u2019 miracle rally tops Packers, earns Super Bowl trip|url=http://seattletimes.com/html/seahawks/2025494755_seahawksonlinegamer19xml.html|website=Seattle Times|accessdate=January 18, 2015}}</ref> In his postgame interview, Bostick acknowledged that he was supposed to block so that [[Jordy Nelson]] could recover the onside kick.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wood |first1=Ryan |title=Bostick admits play for onside kick 'not my job' |url=http://www.greenbaypressgazette.com/story/sports/nfl/packers/2015/01/18/bostick-admits-play-for-onside-kick-not-my-job/21976159/ |website=Green Bay Press-Gazette |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ViShFXk9?url=http://www.greenbaypressgazette.com/story/sports/nfl/packers/2015/01/18/bostick-admits-play-for-onside-kick-not-my-job/21976159/ |archivedate=January 20, 2015 |date=January 19, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Bostick was released on February 16, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fantasynews.cbssports.com/fantasyfootball/update/25070773/packers-release-nfc-title-game-goat-brandon-bostick|title=Packers release NFC title game goat Brandon Bostick|last=Krest|first=Shawn|work=fantasynews.cbssports.com|date=February 16, 2015|accessdate=February 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Minnesota Vikings===\nBostick was claimed off waivers by the [[Minnesota Vikings]] on February 18, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000471264/article/vikings-claim-brandon-bostick-off-waivers|title=Vikings claim tight end Brandon Bostick off waivers|first=Nick|last=Shook|work=NFL.com|date=February 18, 2015|accessdate=February 18, 2015}}</ref> Bostick was released by the Vikings as part of the first wave of roster cuts on August 30, 2015.\n\n===Arizona Cardinals===\nOn September 7, 2015, the [[Arizona Cardinals]] signed Bostick to their practice squad.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180301044621/http://www.azcardinals.com/news-and-events/article-2/Practice-Squad-Set-For-Cardinals/0e6435c2-45b2-4b05-aea5-e7234141db91 |title=Practice Squad Set For Cardinals |last=Urban |first=Darren |date=September 7, 2015 |website=AZCardinals.com |accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> On September 22, 2015, he was released by the Cardinals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.azcardinals.com/2015/09/22/kerwynn-williams-cut-as-massie-returns/ |title=Kerwynn Williams cut as Massie returns |last=Urban |first=Darren |date=September 22, 2015 |website=AZCardinals.com |accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref> On October 2, 2015, Bostick was re-signed to the Cardinals' practice squad.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.azcardinals.com/news-and-events/article-2/Looking-To-Break-Out-Michael-Floyd/f12622a4-3959-425b-b9b4-c9d2eb3cade3 |title=Looking To Break Out Michael Floyd |last=Urban |first=Darren |date=October 2, 2015 |website=AZCardinals.com |accessdate=October 5, 2015}}</ref> On December 1, 2015, he was released from practice squad.\n\n===New York Jets===\nOn December 8, 2015, the [[New York Jets]] signed Bostick to their practice squad.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lange|first1=Randy|title=Jets Place DE Mike Catapano (Foot) on IR|url=http://www.newyorkjets.com/news/article-9/Jets-Place-DE-Mike-Catapano-Foot-on-IR/d93d4a78-b869-4698-9073-72ef3161a0f3|website=NewYorkJets.com|accessdate=December 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n''Source: [http://www.nfl.com/player/brandonbostick/2536342/profile NFL.com]''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year !! rowspan=\"2\"|Team !! rowspan=\"2\"|G !! rowspan=\"2\"|GS !! colspan=\"5\"|Receiving !! colspan=\"2\"|Fumbles\n|-\n! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Fum !! Lost\n|-\n! colspan=11|'''Regular season'''\n|-\n! [[2013 NFL season|2013]] !! [[2013 Green Bay Packers season|GB]]\n| 11 || 0 || 7 || 120 || 17.1 || 26 || 1 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2014 NFL season|2014]] !! [[2014 Green Bay Packers season|GB]]\n| 13 || 0 || 2 || 3 || 1.5 || 2 || 1 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] !! [[2016 New York Jets season|NYJ]]\n| 16 || 7 || 8 || 63 || 7.9 || 14 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total || 40 || 7 || 17 || 186 || 10.9 || 26 || 2 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=11|'''Postseason'''\n|-\n! [[2014\u201315 NFL playoffs|2014]] !! [[2014 Green Bay Packers season|GB]]\n| 2 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"|Total || 2 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nHis cousin, [[Akeem Bostick]], plays in [[Minor League Baseball]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rangersblog.dallasnews.com/2013/06/meet-the-rangers-third-draft-pick-rhp-akeem-bostic.html/|title=Meet the Rangers\u2019 third draft pick: RHP Akeem Bostic|work=Texas Rangers Blog|accessdate=January 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.packers.com/team/roster/brandon-bostick/855d5326-2230-4a0b-9f22-20b58a40a56b Green Bay Packers bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bostick, Brandon}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Florence, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:American football tight ends]]\n[[Category:Newberry Wolves football players]]\n[[Category:Green Bay Packers players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings players]]\n[[Category:Arizona Cardinals players]]\n[[Category:New York Jets players]]\n", "name_user": "2607:fea8:1d20:56e9:19b8:f00c:9086:11f8", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brandon_Bostick"}
{"title_page": "Ghigi (cycling team)", "text_new": "{{Infobox cycling team\n| name           = Ghigi\n| image          = Ghigi cycling team 1959.jpg\n| caption        = The Ghigi\u2013Ganna team of 1959\n| code           = \n| registered     = Italy\n| founded        = {{start date|1958}}\n| disbanded      = 1962\n| generalmanager = [[Luciano Pezzi]] (1960\u20131962)\n| discipline     = [[Road bicycle racing|Road]]\n| status         = \n| bicycles       = [[Fausto Coppi|Coppi]] (1958)<br>Ganna (1959)\n| season         = 1958<br>1959<br>1960\u20131962\n| oldname        = Ghigi\u2013Coppi<br>Ghigi\u2013Ganna<br>Ghigi\n| kitimage       = \n}}\n'''Ghigi''' was an Italian professional [[cycling team]] that existed from 1958 to 1962, leading to the formation of the [[Salvarani (cycling team)|Salvarani]] team in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|title=Acc\u00e8s \u00e9quipes Ghigi|url=http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.eu/pelotons/lexsponsors.php?l=Ghigi|language=French|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|accessdate=9 February 2017}}</ref> Its main sponsor was Italian pasta manufacturer Ghigi.<ref>{{cite web|title=A directory of pro cycling team sponsors, old and new|url=http://www.bikeraceinfo.com/riderhistories/sponsors-directory.html|access-date=9 February 2017|work=BikeRaceInfo|publisher=McGann Publishing}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Ghigi cycling team|Ghigi (cycling team)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghigi (cycling team)}}\n[[Category:Cycling teams based in Italy]]\n[[Category:Defunct cycling teams based in Italy]]\n[[Category:1958 establishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:1962 disestablishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:Cycling teams established in 1958]]\n[[Category:Cycling teams disestablished in 1962]]\n\n\n{{cycling-team-stub}}\n{{Italy-sport-team-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cycling team\n| name           = Ghigi\n| image          = Ghigi cycling team 1959.jpg\n| caption        = The Ghigi\u2013Ganna team of 1959\n| code           = \n| registered     = Italy\n| founded        = {{start date|1958}}\n| disbanded      = 1962\n| generalmanager = [[Luciano Pezzi]] (1960\u20131962)\n| discipline     = [[Road bicycle racing|Road]]\n| status         = \n| bicycles       = [[Fausto Coppi|Coppi]] (1958)<br>Ganna (1959)\n| season         = 1958<br>1959<br>1960\u20131962\n| oldname        = Ghigi\u2013Coppi<br>Ghigi\u2013Ganna<br>Ghigi\n| kitimage       = \n}}\n'''Ghigi''' was an Italian professional [[cycling team]] that existed from 1958 to 1962, leading to the formation of the [[Salvarani (cycling team)|Salvarani]] team in 1963.<ref>{{cite web|title=Acc\u00e8s \u00e9quipes Ghigi|url=http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.eu/pelotons/lexsponsors.php?l=Ghigi|language=French|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|accessdate=9 February 2017}}</ref> Its main sponsor was Italian pasta manufacturer Ghigi.<ref>{{cite web|title=A directory of pro cycling team sponsors, old and new|url=http://www.bikeraceinfo.com/riderhistories/sponsors-directory.html|access-date=9 February 2017|work=BikeRaceInfo|publisher=McGann Publishing}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Ghigi cycling team}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ghigi (cycling team)}}\n[[Category:Cycling teams based in Italy]]\n[[Category:Defunct cycling teams based in Italy]]\n[[Category:1958 establishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:1962 disestablishments in Italy]]\n[[Category:Cycling teams established in 1958]]\n[[Category:Cycling teams disestablished in 1962]]\n\n\n{{cycling-team-stub}}\n{{Italy-sport-team-stub}}\n", "name_user": "BaldBoris", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ghigi_(cycling_team)"}
{"title_page": "Frodo Baggins", "text_new": "{{redirect|Frodo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name      = Frodo Baggins\n| image     = File:Frodo CSC pic.jpg\n| caption   = Joe Sofranko as Frodo in a musical comedy from ''The Lord of the Rings'' in [[Cincinnati]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clearstagecincinnati.com/rotk/index.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-08-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009053725/http://www.clearstagecincinnati.com/rotk/index.html |archivedate=2007-10-09 }}</ref><ref>http://www.playbill.com/news/article/lord-of-the-rings-musical-will-embark-on-2015-world-tour-211617</ref>\n| series    = [[J. R. R. Tolkien|Tolkien]]\n| first     = ''[[The Fellowship of the Ring]]'' (1954)\n| last      = ''[[Bilbo's Last Song]]'' (1974)\n| portrayer = \n| aliases   = Mr. Underhill\n| race      = [[Hobbit]]\n| lbl24     = Book(s)\n| data24    = ''[[The Fellowship of the Ring]]''<br/>''[[The Two Towers]]''<br/>''[[The Return of the King]]''<br/>''[[The Silmarillion]]''<br/>''[[Unfinished Tales]]''\n}}\n'''Frodo Baggins''' is a [[Character (arts)|fictional character]] in [[J. R. R. Tolkien]]'s writings, and a protagonist of ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''. Frodo is a [[hobbit]] of [[Shire (Middle-earth)|the Shire]] who inherits the [[One Ring]] from his cousin [[Bilbo Baggins]] and undertakes the quest to destroy it in the fires of [[Mount Doom]] in [[Mordor]]. He is mentioned in Tolkien's posthumously published works, ''[[The Silmarillion]]'' and ''[[Unfinished Tales]]''. \n\nFrodo is repeatedly wounded during the quest, and becomes increasingly burdened by the Ring as it nears Mordor. He changes, too, growing in understanding and compassion, and avoiding violence.\n\nFrodo's name comes from the [[Old English]] name ''[[Froda|Fr\u00f3da]]'', meaning \"wise by experience\". Commentators have written that he combines courage, selflessness, and fidelity, and that as a good character, he seems unexciting but grows through his quest, an unheroic person who reaches heroic stature.\n\n==Internal history==\n\n===Background===\n\nIn ''[[The Hobbit]]'', the protagonist [[Bilbo Baggins]] is taken by the Wizard Gandalf and a party of [[Dwarves (Middle-earth)|Dwarves]] from his safe home, [[Bag End]], in [[Shire (Middle-earth)|the Shire]] across the [[Misty Mountains]] and the dark forest of [[Mirkwood]] to recapture the Dwarves' ancient home and treasure under the Lonely Mountain. The treasure is guarded by a [[Dragon (Middle-earth)|dragon]], [[Smaug]]. Through many adventures, Smaug is killed and Bilbo returns home with a substantial portion of the treasure. He lives the life of a rich eccentric for many years.\n\nFrodo is introduced in ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'' as Bilbo's relative and adoptive heir. The chapter \"A Long-expected Party\" relates that Frodo's parents Drogo Baggins and Primula Brandybuck had been killed in a boating accident when Frodo was 12; Frodo spent the next nine years living with his maternal family, the Brandybucks in Brandy Hall. At the age of 21 he was adopted by his cousin,{{efn|Although Frodo referred to Bilbo as his \"uncle\", they were in fact first ''and'' second cousins, once removed either way (his paternal great-great-uncle's son's son and his maternal great-aunt's son).}} Bilbo, who brought him to live at Bag End. He and Bilbo shared the same birthday, the 22nd of 'September'. Bilbo introduced Frodo to the [[Elvish languages (Middle-earth)|Elvish languages]] , and they often went on long walking trips together.\n\n===''The Fellowship of the Ring''===\n\nFrodo comes of age as Bilbo leaves the Shire for good on his one hundred and eleventh birthday. Frodo inherits Bag End and [[One Ring|Bilbo's ring]]. [[Gandalf]], at this time, is not certain about the origin of the ring, so he warns Frodo to avoid using it and to keep it secret. Frodo keeps the Ring hidden for the next 17 years, and the Ring gives him the same longevity it gave Bilbo. Gandalf returns to prove to him that it is the One Ring of the Dark Lord [[Sauron]], who seeks to recover and use it to conquer [[Middle-earth]].\n\nRealizing that he is a danger to the Shire as long as he remains there with the Ring, Frodo decides to take it to [[Rivendell]], home of [[Elrond]], a mighty [[Elf (Middle-earth)|Elf]]-lord. He leaves with three companions: his gardener [[Samwise Gamgee]] and his cousins [[Merry Brandybuck]] and [[Pippin Took]]. They escape just in time, for Sauron's most powerful servants, the Nine [[Nazg\u00fbl]], have entered the Shire as Black Riders, looking for Bilbo and the Ring. They follow Frodo's trail across the Shire and nearly intercept him.\n\nThe hobbits escape the Black Riders by travelling through the [[Old Forest]]. They are waylaid by the magic of [[Old Man Willow]], but rescued by [[Tom Bombadil]], who gives them shelter and guides them on their way. They are caught in fog on the Barrow Downs by [[Barrow-wight]]s and are entranced under a spell. Frodo breaks loose from the spell, attacks the barrow-wight and summons Bombadil, who again rescues the hobbits and sets them on their way.\n\nAt the ''Prancing Pony'' inn in the village of [[Bree (Middle-earth)|Bree]], Frodo receives a delayed letter from Gandalf, and meets a man who calls himself Strider, a [[Ranger of the North]]; his real name is [[Aragorn]]. The One Ring slips onto Frodo's finger inadvertently in the inn's common room, turning Frodo invisible. This attracts the attention of Sauron's agents, who ransack the hobbits' rooms in the night. The group, under Strider's guidance, flees through the marshes.\n\nWhile encamped on a hill, they are attacked by five Nazg\u00fbl. The chief of the Nazg\u00fbl stabs Frodo with a Morgul-blade; Aragorn routs them with fire. A piece of the blade remains in Frodo's shoulder and, working its way towards his heart, threatens to turn him into a wraith under control of the Nazgul. With the help of his companions and an Elf-lord, [[Glorfindel]], Frodo is able to evade the Nazg\u00fbl and reach Rivendell. Nearly overcome by his wound, he is healed over time by Elrond.\n\nThe [[Council of Elrond]] meets in Rivendell and resolves to destroy the Ring by casting it into [[Mount Doom]] in [[Mordor]], the realm of Sauron. Frodo, realizing that he is destined for this task, steps forward to be the [[Ring-bearer]]. A [[Fellowship of the Ring (characters)|Fellowship of nine companions]] is formed to guide and protect him: the hobbits, Gandalf, Aragorn, the [[dwarf (Middle-earth)|dwarf]] [[Gimli (Middle-earth)|Gimli]], the [[Elf (Middle-earth)|elf]] [[Legolas]], and [[Boromir]], a man of [[Gondor]]. Together they set out from Rivendell. Frodo is armed with [[Sting (Middle-earth)|Sting]], Bilbo's Elvish knife; he wears Bilbo's coat of Dwarf mail made of ''[[mithril]]''. The company, seeking a way through the Misty Mountains, tries the Pass of Caradhras, but abandons it in favour of the [[Moria (Middle-earth)|mines of Moria]]. In Moria Frodo is stabbed by an [[Orc (Middle-earth)|Orc]]-spear, but his coat of ''mithril'' armour saves his life. They are led through the mines by Gandalf, until he is killed battling a [[Balrog]]. Aragorn leads them out to [[Lothl\u00f3rien]]. There [[Galadriel]] gives Frodo an Elven cloak and a phial carrying the Light of [[E\u00e4rendil]] to aid him on his dangerous quest.\n\nThe Fellowship travel by boat down the Anduin River and reach the hills of Parth Galen. There, Boromir, succumbing to the lure of the Ring, tries to take the ring by force from Frodo. Frodo escapes by putting on the Ring and becoming invisible. This breaks the Fellowship; the company is scattered by invading Orcs. Frodo chooses to continue the quest alone, but Sam follows his master, joining him on the journey to Mordor.\n\n===''The Two Towers''===\nFrodo and Sam make their way through the wilds, followed by the creature [[Gollum]], who has been tracking the Fellowship since Moria, seeking to reclaim the Ring. Gollum attacks the hobbits, but Frodo subdues him with Sting. He takes pity on Gollum and spares his life, binding him to a promise to guide them through the dead marshes to the Black Gate, which Gollum does. They find the gate impassable, but Gollum says that there is \"another way\" into Mordor, and Frodo, over Sam's objections, allows him to lead them south into [[Ithilien]]. There they meet [[Faramir]], younger brother of Boromir, who takes them to Henneth Ann\u00fbn. Frodo allows Gollum to be captured by Faramir, saving Gollum's life but leaving him feeling betrayed by his \"master\". Faramir provisions the hobbits and allows them to go on their way, but warns Frodo to beware of Gollum's treachery.\n\nThe three of them pass near Minas Morgul, where the pull of the Ring becomes almost unbearable. There they began the long climb up the Endless Stair, and at the top enter a tunnel, not knowing it is the home of the giant spider [[Shelob]]. Gollum hopes to deliver the hobbits to her and retake the Ring after she kills them. Shelob stings Frodo, rendering him unconscious, but Sam drives her off with Sting and the Phial of Galadriel. After attempting unsuccessfully to wake Frodo up, and unable to find any signs of life, Sam concludes that Frodo is dead and decides that his only option is to take the Ring and continue the quest. But he overhears orcs who find Frodo's body and learns that Frodo is not dead. The orcs take Frodo for questioning; Sam tries to follow but finds the door locked against him.\n\n===''The Return of the King''===\nSam rescues Frodo from the Orcs. After a brief confrontation in which Frodo becomes enraged that Sam has taken the Ring, Sam restores the Ring to Frodo. The two of them, dressed in scavenged Orc-armour, set off for Mount Doom, trailed by Gollum. They witness the plains of Mordor empty at the approach of the Armies of the West. As the Ring gets closer to its master, Frodo becomes progressively weaker as its influence grows. When they run out of water, they leave all unnecessary baggage behind to travel light. As they reach Mount Doom, Gollum reappears and attacks Frodo, who beats him back. While Sam fights with Gollum, Frodo enters the chasm in the volcano where Sauron forged the Ring. Here Frodo loses the will to destroy the Ring, and instead puts it on, claiming it for himself. Gollum pushes Sam aside and attacks the invisible Frodo, biting off his finger. As he dances around in elation, Gollum loses his balance and falls with the Ring into the fiery Cracks of Doom. The Ring is destroyed, and with it Sauron's power. Frodo and Sam are rescued by Gandalf and several [[Eagle (Middle-earth)|Great Eagles]] as Mount Doom erupts.\n\nAfter reuniting with the Fellowship and attending Aragorn's coronation as King of Gondor, the four hobbits return to the Shire. They find the entire Shire in a state of upheaval. Saruman's agents\u2014both Hobbits and [[Man (Middle-earth)|Men]]\u2014have taken it over and started a destructive process of industrialization. Saruman governs the Shire in secret under the name of Sharkey until Frodo and his companions [[The Scouring of the Shire|lead a rebellion and defeat the intruders]]. Even after Saruman attempts to stab Frodo, Frodo lets him go.<ref group=T>''The Return of the King'', Book VI, VII, and VIII, pp. 315\u2013317 and 360\u2013363</ref> Frodo and his companions restore the Shire to its prior state of peace and goodwill. Frodo never completely recovers from the physical, emotional, and psychological wounds he suffered during the quest to destroy the ring. Two years after the Ring was destroyed, Frodo and Bilbo as Ring-bearers are granted passage to [[Valinor]], the [[Earthly Paradise|earthly paradise]] where Frodo might find peace.\n\n===\"The Sea-Bell\"===\n\n\"[[The Sea-Bell]]\" was published in Tolkien's 1962 collection of verse ''[[The Adventures of Tom Bombadil]]'' with the sub-title ''Frodos Dream''. Tolkien suggests that this enigmatic [[narrative poem]] represents the despairing dreams that visited Frodo in the Shire in the years following the destruction of the Ring. It relates the unnamed speaker's journey to a mysterious land across the sea, where he tries but fails to make contact with the people who dwell there. He descends into despair and near-madness, eventually returning to his own country, to find himself utterly alienated from those he once knew.\n\n==Concept and creation==\n\nFrodo did not appear until the third draft of ''A Long-Expected Party'' (the first chapter of ''The Lord of the Rings''), when he was named Bingo, son of Bilbo Baggins and Primula Brandybuck.<ref group=T>''The Return of the Shadow'', Vol. VI in ''The History of Middle-earth'', p. 28\u201329.</ref> In the fourth draft, he was renamed Bingo Bolger-Baggins, son of Rollo Bolger and Primula Brandybuck.<ref group=T>''The Return of the Shadow'', pp. 36\u201337.</ref> Tolkien did not change the name to Frodo until the third phase of writing, when much of the narrative, as far as the hobbits' arrival in Rivendell, had already taken shape.<ref group=T>''The Return of the Shadow'', p. 309.</ref> Prior to this, the name \"Frodo\" had been used for the character who eventually became Pippin Took.<ref group=T>''The Return of the Shadow'', p. 267.</ref>\n\nIn early drafts of ''The Lord of the Rings'' the principal character is called Bingo Baggins; the name Frodo is given to another hobbit. In drafts of the final chapters of ''The Lord of the Rings'' published as ''[[Sauron Defeated]]'', Gandalf names Frodo ''Bronwe athan Harthad'' (\"Endurance Beyond Hope\"), after the destruction of the Ring. Tolkien states that Frodo's name in [[Westron]] was ''Maura Labingi''.<ref group=T>Tolkien, Christopher. ''The History of Middle-earth'', Volume XII, ''The Peoples of Middle-earth'', \"The Appendix on Languages\", pp. 48, 50.</ref> The [[Sindarin]] version was ''Iorhael'',<ref group=T>The name of Sam's son Frodo appears as ''Iorhael'' in the [[Tengwar]] version of the King's Letter to Sam. Christopher Tolkien, ''The History of Middle-earth'', Volume IX, ''Sauron Defeated'', \"The Epilogue\", pp. 117, 126, 128, 130, 131.</ref> (\"Old and Wise\"). In ''The Return of the King'' he is also called ''Daur'', Sindarin for \"noble\".<ref group=T>''[[The Return of the King]]'' by [[J. R. R. Tolkien]]</ref>\n\n==Interpretations== \n\nFrodo is the only prominent hobbit whose name is not explained in Tolkien's Appendices to ''The Lord of the Rings''. In a letter Tolkien states that it is the [[Old English]] name ''[[Froda|Fr\u00f3da]]'', connected to ''[[Germanic name#Frod|fr\u00f3d]]'', \"wise by experience\".<ref group=T>''[[Letters of J. R. R. Tolkien|Letters]]'', #168</ref> The Tolkien scholar [[Tom Shippey]] suggests that the choice of name is significant: not, in Tolkien's phrase, one of the many \"names that had no meaning at all in [the hobbits'] daily language\".{{sfn|Shippey|2005|pp=231-237}} Instead, he notes, the [[Old Norse]] name ''[[Fr\u00f3\u00f0i]]'' is mentioned in ''[[Beowulf]]'' as the minor character ''Fr\u00f3da''. ''Fr\u00f3\u00f0i'' was, he writes, said by [[Saxo Grammaticus]] and [[Snorri Sturluson]] to be a peaceful ruler at the time of Christ, his time being named the ''Fr\u00f3\u00f0a-fri\u00f0'', the peace of ''Fr\u00f3\u00f0i''. This was created by his magic mill, worked by two female giants, that could churn out peace and gold. He makes the giants work all day long at this task, until they rebel and grind out an army instead, which kills him and takes over, making the giants grind salt until the sea is full of it. The name ''Fr\u00f3\u00f0i'' is forgotten. Clearly, Shippey observes, evil is impossible to cure; and Frodo too is a \"peacemaker, indeed in the end a [[pacifist]]\".{{sfn|Shippey|2005|pp=231-237}} And, he writes, as Frodo gains experience through the quest, he also gains wisdom, matching the meaning of his name.{{sfn|Shippey|2005|pp=231-237}}\n\nMichael Stanton, writing in the ''[[J.R.R. Tolkien Encyclopedia]]'', describes Frodo's character as combining \"courage, selflessness, and fidelity\",{{sfn|Stanton|2013|pp=223\u2013225}} attributes that make Frodo ideal as a Ring-bearer. He lacks Sam's simple sturdiness, Merry and Pippin's clowning, and the [[psychopathology]] of Gollum, writes Stanton, bearing out the saying that good is less exciting than evil; but Frodo grows through his quest, becoming \"ennobled\" by it, to the extent that returning to the Shire feels in Frodo's words \"like falling asleep again\".{{sfn|Stanton|2013|pp=223\u2013225}}\n\nThe Tolkien scholar [[Jane Chance]] quotes [[Randel Helms]]'s view that in both ''The Hobbit'' and ''Lord of the Rings'', \"a most unheroic hobbit achieves heroic stature\" in a quest romance.{{sfn|Nitzsche|1980|pp=97-98}}{{sfn|Helms|1974|p=21}} Chance writes that Frodo grows from seeing the threat as external, such as from the Black Riders, to internal, whether within the Fellowship, as shown by Boromir's attempt on the Ring, or within himself, as he struggles against the controlling power of the Ring.{{sfn|Nitzsche|1980|p=99}}\n\nThe Tolkien critic [[Paul H. Kocher]] discusses the role of [[Divine providence|providence]], in the form of the intentions of the angel-like [[Valar]] or of the creator [[Eru Il\u00favatar]], in Bilbo's finding of the Ring and Frodo's bearing of it; as Gandalf says, Frodo was \"meant\" to have it, though it remains his choice to co-operate with this purpose.{{sfn|Kocher|1974|p=37}}\n\n==Adaptations==\n[[File:BakshiFrodo.JPG|left|thumb|200px|Frodo in [[Ralph Bakshi]]'s animated version of ''[[The Lord of the Rings (1978 film)|The Lord of the Rings]]'']]\n[[File:Elijah Wood as Frodo Baggins.png|right|thumb|[[Elijah Wood]] as Frodo Baggins in [[Peter Jackson]]'s ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring]]'']]\n\nIn [[Ralph Bakshi]]'s 1978 [[The Lord of the Rings (1978 film)|animated version]] of ''The Lord of the Rings'', Frodo was voiced by [[Christopher Guard]].\n\nIn the 1980 [[Rankin/Bass]] animated version of ''[[The Return of the King (1980 film)|The Return of the King]]'', made for television, the character was voiced by [[Orson Bean]], who had previously played Bilbo in the same company's adaptation of ''[[The Hobbit (1977 film)|The Hobbit]]''.\n\nIn the 1981 [[BBC]] radio [[The Lord of the Rings (1981 radio series)|serial of ''The Lord of the Rings'']], Frodo is played by [[Ian Holm]], who later played Bilbo in [[Peter Jackson]]'s [[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|film adaptation]] of ''The Lord of the Rings''.\n\nIn the 1993 television [[miniseries]] ''[[Hobitit]]'' by Finnish broadcaster [[Yle]], Frodo is played by Taneli M\u00e4kel\u00e4.\n\nIn ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'' film trilogy (2001\u20132003) directed by [[Peter Jackson]], Frodo is played by American actor [[Elijah Wood]]. Dan Timmons writes in the [[Mythopoeic Society]]'s ''Tolkien on Film: Essays on Peter Jackson\u2019s The Lord of the Rings'' (Mythopoeic Press, 2005) that the themes and internal logic of the Jackson films are undermined by the portrayal of Frodo, whom he considers a weakening of Tolkien's original.<ref name=\"timmons\">{{cite book |last=Timmons |first=Dan |chapter=Frodo on Film: Peter Jackson\u2019s Problematic Portrayal |title=Tolkien on Film: Essays on Peter Jackson's The Lord of the Rings |editor-last=Croft |editor-first=Janet Brennan |publisher=[[Mythopoeic Society|Mythopoeic Press]] |chapter-url=http://www.mythsoc.org/press/tolkien.on.film/ |year=2005 |location=Altadena |isbn=978-1-887726-09-2 |accessdate=2009-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090923204958/http://www.mythsoc.org/press/tolkien.on.film/ |archivedate=23 September 2009 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nElijah Wood reprised his role of Frodo in a brief appearance in ''[[The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey Pics: Elijah Wood Returns as Frodo; Martin Freeman's Bilbo Gets His Sword |url=http://au.eonline.com/news/355189/new-hobbit-an-unexpected-journey-pics-elijah-wood-returns-as-frodo-martin-freeman-s-bilbo-gets-his-sword |accessdate=26 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn stage, Frodo was portrayed by [[James Loye]] in the three-hour stage production of ''[[Lord of the Rings (musical)|The Lord of the Rings]]'', which opened in [[Toronto]] in 2006, and was brought to London in 2007. In the United States, Frodo was portrayed by [[Joe Sofranko]] in the [[Cincinnati]] productions of ''The Fellowship of the Ring'' (2001), ''The Two Towers'' (2002), and ''The Return of the King'' (2003) for [[Clear Stage Cincinnati]]. In Chicago, [[Patrick Blashill]] played Frodo in the [[Lifeline Theatre]] production of ''The Two Towers'' in 1999.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Speculative fiction}}\n* [[Rings of Power]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Primary===\n::''This list identifies each item's location in Tolkien's writings.''\n{{reflist|group=T|28em}}\n\n===Secondary===\n{{reflist|28em}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n* {{cite book |last=Helms |first=Randel |authorlink=Randel Helms |title=Tolkien's World |date=1974 |publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin]] |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kocher |first=Paul |authorlink=Paul H. Kocher |title=Master of Middle-Earth: The Achievement of J.R.R. Tolkien |date=1974 |origyear=1972 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=0140038779 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Nitzsche |first=Jane Chance |authorlink=Jane Chance |title=Tolkien's Art |date=1980 |origyear=1979 |publisher=Papermac |isbn=0-333-29034-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Shippey |first=Tom |authorlink=Tom Shippey |title=The Road to Middle-Earth |date=2005 |edition=Third |origyear=1982 |publisher=HarperCollins |isbn=978-0261102750 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |last=Stanton |first=Michael N. |editor-last=Drout |editor-first=Michael D. C. |editor-link=Michael D. C. Drout |title=Frodo |work=[[J.R.R. Tolkien Encyclopedia|J.R.R. Tolkien Encyclopedia: Scholarship and Critical Assessment]] |year=2013 |origyear=2007 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |isbn=978-0-415-86511-1 |pages=223\u2013225 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{The Lord of the Rings}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baggins, Frodo}}\n[[Category:The Lord of the Rings characters]]\n[[Category:Middle-earth Hobbits]]\n[[Category:Adventure film characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional orphans]]\n[[Category:Bearers of the One Ring]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who can turn invisible]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1954]]\n[[Category:Fictional swordsmen]]\n[[Category:Fictional amputees]]\n[[Category:Fictional writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Frodo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name      = Frodo Baggins\n| image     = File:Frodo CSC pic.jpg\n| caption   = Joe Sofranko as Frodo in a musical comedy from ''The Lord of the Rings'' in [[Cincinnati]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.clearstagecincinnati.com/rotk/index.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-08-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009053725/http://www.clearstagecincinnati.com/rotk/index.html |archivedate=2007-10-09 }}</ref><ref>http://www.playbill.com/news/article/lord-of-the-rings-musical-will-embark-on-2015-world-tour-211617</ref>\n| series    = [[J. R. R. Tolkien|Tolkien]]\n| first     = ''[[The Fellowship of the Ring]]'' (1954)\n| last      = ''[[Bilbo's Last Song]]'' (1974)\n| portrayer = \n| aliases   = Mr. Underhill\n| race      = [[Hobbit]]\n| lbl24     = Book(s)\n| data24    = ''[[The Fellowship of the Ring]]''<br/>''[[The Two Towers]]''<br/>''[[The Return of the King]]''<br/>''[[The Silmarillion]]''<br/>''[[Unfinished Tales]]''\n}}\n'''Frodo Baggins''' is a [[Character (arts)|fictional character]] in [[J. R. R. Tolkien]]'s writings, and a protagonist of ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]''. Frodo is a [[hobbit]] of [[Shire (Middle-earth)|the Shire]] who inherits the [[One Ring]] from his cousin [[Bilbo Baggins]] and undertakes the quest to destroy it in the fires of [[Mount Doom]] in [[Mordor]]. He is mentioned in Tolkien's posthumously published works, ''[[The Silmarillion]]'' and ''[[Unfinished Tales]]''. \n\nFrodo is repeatedly wounded during the quest, and becomes increasingly burdened by the Ring as it nears Mordor. He changes, too, growing in understanding and compassion, and avoiding violence.\n\nFrodo's name comes from the [[Old English]] name ''[[Froda|Fr\u00f3da]]'', meaning \"wise by experience\". Commentators have written that he combines courage, selflessness, and fidelity, and that as a good character, he seems unexciting but grows through his quest, an unheroic person who reaches heroic stature.\n\n==Internal history==\n\n===Background===\n\nIn ''[[The Hobbit]]'', the protagonist [[Bilbo Baggins]] is taken by the Wizard Gandalf and a party of [[Dwarves (Middle-earth)|Dwarves]] from his safe home, [[Bag End]], in [[Shire (Middle-earth)|the Shire]] across the [[Misty Mountains]] and the dark forest of [[Mirkwood]] to recapture the Dwarves' ancient home and treasure under the Lonely Mountain. The treasure is guarded by a [[Dragon (Middle-earth)|dragon]], [[Smaug]]. Through many adventures, Smaug is killed and Bilbo returns home with a substantial portion of the treasure. He lives the life of a rich eccentric for many years.\n\nFrodo is introduced in ''[[The Lord of the Rings]]'' as Bilbo's relative and adoptive heir. The chapter \"A Long-expected Party\" relates that Frodo's parents Drogo Baggins and Primula Brandybuck had been killed in a boating accident when Frodo was 12; Frodo spent the next nine years living with his maternal family, the Brandybucks in Brandy Hall. At the age of 21 he was adopted by his cousin,{{efn|Although Frodo referred to Bilbo as his \"uncle\", they were in fact first ''and'' second cousins, once removed either way (his paternal great-great-uncle's son's son and his maternal great-aunt's son).}} Bilbo, who brought him to live at Bag End. He and Bilbo shared the same birthday, the 22nd of 'September'. Bilbo introduced Frodo to the [[Elvish languages (Middle-earth)|Elvish languages]] , and they often went on long walking trips together.\n\n===''The Fellowship of the Ring''===\n\nFrodo comes of age as Bilbo leaves the Shire for good on his one hundred and eleventh birthday. Frodo inherits Bag End and [[One Ring|Bilbo's ring]]. [[Gandalf]], at this time, is not certain about the origin of the ring, so he warns Frodo to avoid using it and to keep it secret. Frodo keeps the Ring hidden for the next 17 years, and the Ring gives him the same longevity it gave Bilbo. Gandalf returns to prove to him that it is the One Ring of the Dark Lord [[Sauron]], who seeks to recover and use it to conquer [[Middle-earth]].\n\nRealizing that he is a danger to the Shire as long as he remains there with the Ring, Frodo decides to take it to [[Rivendell]], home of [[Elrond]], a mighty [[Elf (Middle-earth)|Elf]]-lord. He leaves with three companions: his gardener [[Samwise Gamgee]] and his cousins [[Merry Brandybuck]] and [[Pippin Took]]. They escape just in time, for Sauron's most powerful servants, the Nine [[Nazg\u00fbl]], have entered the Shire as Black Riders, looking for Bilbo and the Ring. They follow Frodo's trail across the Shire and nearly intercept him.\n\nThe hobbits escape the Black Riders by travelling through the [[Old Forest]]. They are waylaid by the magic of [[Old Man Willow]], but rescued by [[Tom Bombadil]], who gives them shelter and guides them on their way. They are caught in fog on the Barrow Downs by [[Barrow-wight]]s and are entranced under a spell. Frodo breaks loose from the spell, attacks the barrow-wight and summons Bombadil, who again rescues the hobbits and sets them on their way.\n\nAt the ''Prancing Pony'' inn in the village of [[Bree (Middle-earth)|Bree]], Frodo receives a delayed letter from Gandalf, and meets a man who calls himself Strider, a [[Ranger of the North]]; his real name is [[Aragorn]]. The One Ring slips onto Frodo's finger inadvertently in the inn's common room, turning Frodo invisible. This attracts the attention of Sauron's agents, who ransack the hobbits' rooms in the night. The group, under Strider's guidance, flees through the marshes.\n\nWhile encamped on a hill, they are attacked by five Nazg\u00fbl. The chief of the Nazg\u00fbl stabs Frodo with a Morgul-blade; Aragorn routs them with fire. A piece of the blade remains in Frodo's shoulder and, working its way towards his heart, threatens to turn him into a wraith under control of the Nazgul. With the help of his companions and an Elf-lord, [[Glorfindel]], Frodo is able to evade the Nazg\u00fbl and reach Rivendell. Nearly overcome by his wound, he is healed over time by Elrond.\n\nThe [[Council of Elrond]] meets in Rivendell and resolves to destroy the Ring by casting it into [[Mount Doom]] in [[Mordor]], the realm of Sauron. Frodo, realizing that he is destined for this task, steps forward to be the [[Ring-bearer]]. A [[Fellowship of the Ring (characters)|Fellowship of nine companions]] is formed to guide and protect him: the hobbits, Gandalf, Aragorn, the [[dwarf (Middle-earth)|dwarf]] [[Gimli (Middle-earth)|Gimli]], the [[Elf (Middle-earth)|elf]] [[Legolas]], and [[Boromir]], a man of [[Gondor]]. Together they set out from Rivendell. Frodo is armed with [[Sting (Middle-earth)|Sting]], Bilbo's Elvish knife; he wears Bilbo's coat of Dwarf mail made of ''[[mithril]]''. The company, seeking a way through the Misty Mountains, tries the Pass of Caradhras, but abandons it in favour of the [[Moria (Middle-earth)|mines of Moria]]. In Moria Frodo is stabbed by an [[Orc (Middle-earth)|Orc]]-spear, but his coat of ''mithril'' armour saves his life. They are led through the mines by Gandalf, until he is killed battling a [[Balrog]]. Aragornleads them out to [[Lothl\u00f3rien]]. There [[Galadriel]] gives Frodo an Elven cloak and a phial carrying the Light of [[E\u00e4rendil]] to aid him on his dangerous quest.\n\nThe Fellowship travel by boat down the Anduin River and reach the hills of Parth Galen. There, Boromir, succumbing to the lure of the Ring, tries to take the ring by force from Frodo. Frodo escapes by putting on the Ring and becoming invisible. This breaks the Fellowship; the company is scattered by invading Orcs. Frodo chooses to continue the quest alone, but Sam follows his master, joining him on the journey to Mordor.\n\n===''The Two Towers''===\nFrodo and Sam make their way through the wilds, followed by the creature [[Gollum]], who has been tracking the Fellowship since Moria, seeking to reclaim the Ring. Gollum attacks the hobbits, but Frodo subdues him with Sting. He takes pity on Gollum and spares his life, binding him to a promise to guide them through the dead marshes to the Black Gate, which Gollum does. They find the gate impassable, but Gollum says that there is \"another way\" into Mordor, and Frodo, over Sam's objections, allows him to lead them south into [[Ithilien]]. There they meet [[Faramir]], younger brother of Boromir, who takes them to Henneth Ann\u00fbn. Frodo allows Gollum to be captured by Faramir, saving Gollum's life but leaving him feeling betrayed by his \"master\". Faramir provisions the hobbits and allows them to go on their way, but warns Frodo to beware of Gollum's treachery.\n\nThe three of them pass near Minas Morgul, where the pull of the Ring becomes almost unbearable. There they began the long climb up the Endless Stair, and at the top enter a tunnel, not knowing it is the home of the giant spider [[Shelob]]. Gollum hopes to deliver the hobbits to her and retake the Ring after she kills them. Shelob stings Frodo, rendering him unconscious, but Sam drives her off with Sting and the Phial of Galadriel. After attempting unsuccessfully to wake Frodo up, and unable to find any signs of life, Sam concludes that Frodo is dead and decides that his only option is to take the Ring and continue the quest. But he overhears orcs who find Frodo's body and learns that Frodo is not dead. The orcs take Frodo for questioning; Sam tries to follow but finds the door locked against him.\n\n===''The Return of the King''===\nSam rescues Frodo from the Orcs. After a brief confrontation in which Frodo becomes enraged that Sam has taken the Ring, Sam restores the Ring to Frodo. The two of them, dressed in scavenged Orc-armour, set off for Mount Doom, trailed by Gollum. They witness the plains of Mordor empty at the approach of the Armies of the West. As the Ring gets closer to its master, Frodo becomes progressively weaker as its influence grows. When they run out of water, they leave all unnecessary baggage behind to travel light. As they reach Mount Doom, Gollum reappears and attacks Frodo, who beats him back. While Sam fights with Gollum, Frodo enters the chasm in the volcano where Sauron forged the Ring. Here Frodo loses the will to destroy the Ring, and instead puts it on, claiming it for himself. Gollum pushes Sam aside and attacks the invisible Frodo, biting off his finger. As he dances around in elation, Gollum loses his balance and falls with the Ring into the fiery Cracks of Doom. The Ring is destroyed, and with it Sauron's power. Frodo and Sam are rescued by Gandalf and several [[Eagle (Middle-earth)|Great Eagles]] as Mount Doom erupts.\n\nAfter reuniting with the Fellowship and attending Aragorn's coronation as King of Gondor, the four hobbits return to the Shire. They find the entire Shire in a state of upheaval. Saruman's agents\u2014both Hobbits and [[Man (Middle-earth)|Men]]\u2014have taken it over and started a destructive process of industrialization. Saruman governs the Shire in secret under the name of Sharkey until Frodo and his companions [[The Scouring of the Shire|lead a rebellion and defeat the intruders]]. Even after Saruman attempts to stab Frodo, Frodo lets him go.<ref group=T>''The Return of the King'', Book VI, VII, and VIII, pp. 315\u2013317 and 360\u2013363</ref> Frodo and his companions restore the Shire to its prior state of peace and goodwill. Frodo never completely recovers from the physical, emotional, and psychological wounds he suffered during the quest to destroy the ring. Two years after the Ring was destroyed, Frodo and Bilbo as Ring-bearers are granted passage to [[Valinor]], the [[Earthly Paradise|earthly paradise]] where Frodo might find peace.\n\n===\"The Sea-Bell\"===\n\n\"[[The Sea-Bell]]\" was published in Tolkien's 1962 collection of verse ''[[The Adventures of Tom Bombadil]]'' with the sub-title ''Frodos Dream''. Tolkien suggests that this enigmatic [[narrative poem]] represents the despairing dreams that visited Frodo in the Shire in the years following the destruction of the Ring. It relates the unnamed speaker's journey to a mysterious land across the sea, where he tries but fails to make contact with the people who dwell there. He descends into despair and near-madness, eventually returning to his own country, to find himself utterly alienated from those he once knew.\n\n==Concept and creation==\n\nFrodo did not appear until the third draft of ''A Long-Expected Party'' (the first chapter of ''The Lord of the Rings''), when he was named Bingo, son of Bilbo Baggins and Primula Brandybuck.<ref group=T>''The Return of the Shadow'', Vol. VI in ''The History of Middle-earth'', p. 28\u201329.</ref> In the fourth draft, he was renamed Bingo Bolger-Baggins, son of Rollo Bolger and Primula Brandybuck.<ref group=T>''The Return of the Shadow'', pp. 36\u201337.</ref> Tolkien did not change the name to Frodo until the third phase of writing, when much of the narrative, as far as the hobbits' arrival in Rivendell, had already taken shape.<ref group=T>''The Return of the Shadow'', p. 309.</ref> Prior to this, the name \"Frodo\" had been used for the character who eventually became Pippin Took.<ref group=T>''The Return of the Shadow'', p. 267.</ref>\n\nIn early drafts of ''The Lord of the Rings'' the principal character is called Bingo Baggins; the name Frodo is given to another hobbit. In drafts of the final chapters of ''The Lord of the Rings'' published as ''[[Sauron Defeated]]'', Gandalf names Frodo ''Bronwe athan Harthad'' (\"Endurance Beyond Hope\"), after the destruction of the Ring. Tolkien states that Frodo's name in [[Westron]] was ''Maura Labingi''.<ref group=T>Tolkien, Christopher. ''The History of Middle-earth'', Volume XII, ''The Peoples of Middle-earth'', \"The Appendix on Languages\", pp. 48, 50.</ref> The [[Sindarin]] version was ''Iorhael'',<ref group=T>The name of Sam's son Frodo appears as ''Iorhael'' in the [[Tengwar]] version of the King's Letter to Sam. Christopher Tolkien, ''The History of Middle-earth'', Volume IX, ''Sauron Defeated'', \"The Epilogue\", pp. 117, 126, 128, 130, 131.</ref> (\"Old and Wise\"). In ''The Return of the King'' he is also called ''Daur'', Sindarin for \"noble\".<ref group=T>''[[The Return of the King]]'' by [[J. R. R. Tolkien]]</ref>\n\n==Interpretations== \n\nFrodo is the only prominent hobbit whose name is not explained in Tolkien's Appendices to ''The Lord of the Rings''. In a letter Tolkien states that it is the [[Old English]] name ''[[Froda|Fr\u00f3da]]'', connected to ''[[Germanic name#Frod|fr\u00f3d]]'', \"wise by experience\".<ref group=T>''[[Letters of J. R. R. Tolkien|Letters]]'', #168</ref> The Tolkien scholar [[Tom Shippey]] suggests that the choice of name is significant: not, in Tolkien's phrase, one of the many \"names that had no meaning at all in [the hobbits'] daily language\".{{sfn|Shippey|2005|pp=231-237}} Instead, he notes, the [[Old Norse]] name ''[[Fr\u00f3\u00f0i]]'' is mentioned in ''[[Beowulf]]'' as the minor character ''Fr\u00f3da''. ''Fr\u00f3\u00f0i'' was, he writes, said by [[Saxo Grammaticus]] and [[Snorri Sturluson]] to be a peaceful ruler at the time of Christ, his time being named the ''Fr\u00f3\u00f0a-fri\u00f0'', the peace of ''Fr\u00f3\u00f0i''. This was created by his magic mill, worked by two female giants, that could churn out peace and gold. He makes the giants work all day long at this task, until they rebel and grind out an army instead, which kills him and takes over, making the giants grind salt until the sea is full of it. The name ''Fr\u00f3\u00f0i'' is forgotten. Clearly, Shippey observes, evil is impossible to cure; and Frodo too is a \"peacemaker, indeed in the end a [[pacifist]]\".{{sfn|Shippey|2005|pp=231-237}} And, he writes, as Frodo gains experience through the quest, he also gains wisdom, matching the meaning of his name.{{sfn|Shippey|2005|pp=231-237}}\n\nMichael Stanton, writing in the ''[[J.R.R. Tolkien Encyclopedia]]'', describes Frodo's character as combining \"courage, selflessness, and fidelity\",{{sfn|Stanton|2013|pp=223\u2013225}} attributes that make Frodo ideal as a Ring-bearer. He lacks Sam's simple sturdiness, Merry and Pippin's clowning, and the [[psychopathology]] of Gollum, writes Stanton, bearing out the saying that good is less exciting than evil; but Frodo grows through his quest, becoming \"ennobled\" by it, to the extent that returning to the Shire feels in Frodo's words \"like falling asleep again\".{{sfn|Stanton|2013|pp=223\u2013225}}\n\nThe Tolkien scholar [[Jane Chance]] quotes [[Randel Helms]]'s view that in both ''The Hobbit'' and ''Lord of the Rings'', \"a most unheroic hobbit achieves heroic stature\" in a quest romance.{{sfn|Nitzsche|1980|pp=97-98}}{{sfn|Helms|1974|p=21}} Chance writes that Frodo grows from seeing the threat as external, such as from the Black Riders, to internal, whether within the Fellowship, as shown by Boromir's attempt on the Ring, or within himself, as he struggles against the controlling power of the Ring.{{sfn|Nitzsche|1980|p=99}}\n\nThe Tolkien critic [[Paul H. Kocher]] discusses the role of [[Divine providence|providence]], in the form of the intentions of the angel-like [[Valar]] or of the creator [[Eru Il\u00favatar]], in Bilbo's finding of the Ring and Frodo's bearing of it; as Gandalf says, Frodo was \"meant\" to have it, though it remains his choice to co-operate with this purpose.{{sfn|Kocher|1974|p=37}}\n\n==Adaptations==\n[[File:BakshiFrodo.JPG|left|thumb|200px|Frodo in [[Ralph Bakshi]]'s animated version of ''[[The Lord of the Rings (1978 film)|The Lord of the Rings]]'']]\n[[File:Elijah Wood as Frodo Baggins.png|right|thumb|[[Elijah Wood]] as Frodo Baggins in [[Peter Jackson]]'s ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Fellowship of the Ring]]'']]\n\nIn [[Ralph Bakshi]]'s 1978 [[The Lord of the Rings (1978 film)|animated version]] of ''The Lord of the Rings'', Frodo was voiced by [[Christopher Guard]].\n\nIn the 1980 [[Rankin/Bass]] animated version of ''[[The Return of the King (1980 film)|The Return of the King]]'', made for television, the character was voiced by [[Orson Bean]], who had previously played Bilbo in the same company's adaptation of ''[[The Hobbit (1977 film)|The Hobbit]]''.\n\nIn the 1981 [[BBC]] radio [[The Lord of the Rings (1981 radio series)|serial of ''The Lord of the Rings'']], Frodo is played by [[Ian Holm]], who later played Bilbo in [[Peter Jackson]]'s [[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|film adaptation]] of ''The Lord of the Rings''.\n\nIn the 1993 television [[miniseries]] ''[[Hobitit]]'' by Finnish broadcaster [[Yle]], Frodo is played by Taneli M\u00e4kel\u00e4.\n\nIn ''[[The Lord of the Rings (film series)|The Lord of the Rings]]'' film trilogy (2001\u20132003) directed by [[Peter Jackson]], Frodo is played by American actor [[Elijah Wood]]. Dan Timmons writes in the [[Mythopoeic Society]]'s ''Tolkien on Film: Essays on Peter Jackson\u2019s The Lord of the Rings'' (Mythopoeic Press, 2005) that the themes and internal logic of the Jackson films are undermined by the portrayal of Frodo, whom he considers a weakening of Tolkien's original.<ref name=\"timmons\">{{cite book |last=Timmons |first=Dan |chapter=Frodo on Film: Peter Jackson\u2019s Problematic Portrayal |title=Tolkien on Film: Essays on Peter Jackson's The Lord of the Rings |editor-last=Croft |editor-first=Janet Brennan |publisher=[[Mythopoeic Society|Mythopoeic Press]] |chapter-url=http://www.mythsoc.org/press/tolkien.on.film/ |year=2005 |location=Altadena |isbn=978-1-887726-09-2 |accessdate=2009-06-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090923204958/http://www.mythsoc.org/press/tolkien.on.film/ |archivedate=23 September 2009 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nElijah Wood reprised his role of Frodo in a brief appearance in ''[[The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey Pics: Elijah Wood Returns as Frodo; Martin Freeman's Bilbo Gets His Sword |url=http://au.eonline.com/news/355189/new-hobbit-an-unexpected-journey-pics-elijah-wood-returns-as-frodo-martin-freeman-s-bilbo-gets-his-sword |accessdate=26 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn stage, Frodo was portrayed by [[James Loye]] in the three-hour stage production of ''[[Lord of the Rings (musical)|The Lord of the Rings]]'', which opened in [[Toronto]] in 2006, and was brought to London in 2007. In the United States, Frodo was portrayed by [[Joe Sofranko]] in the [[Cincinnati]] productions of ''The Fellowship of the Ring'' (2001), ''The Two Towers'' (2002), and ''The Return of the King'' (2003) for [[Clear Stage Cincinnati]]. In Chicago, [[Patrick Blashill]] played Frodo in the [[Lifeline Theatre]] production of ''The Two Towers'' in 1999.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Speculative fiction}}\n* [[Rings of Power]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n\n===Primary===\n::''This list identifies each item's location in Tolkien's writings.''\n{{reflist|group=T|28em}}\n\n===Secondary===\n{{reflist|28em}}\n\n==Sources==\n\n* {{cite book |last=Helms |first=Randel |authorlink=Randel Helms |title=Tolkien's World |date=1974 |publisher=[[Houghton Mifflin]] |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kocher |first=Paul |authorlink=Paul H. Kocher |title=Master of Middle-Earth: The Achievement of J.R.R. Tolkien |date=1974 |origyear=1972 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=0140038779 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Nitzsche |first=Jane Chance |authorlink=Jane Chance |title=Tolkien's Art |date=1980 |origyear=1979 |publisher=Papermac |isbn=0-333-29034-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Shippey |first=Tom |authorlink=Tom Shippey |title=The Road to Middle-Earth |date=2005 |edition=Third |origyear=1982 |publisher=HarperCollins |isbn=978-0261102750 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia |last=Stanton |first=Michael N. |editor-last=Drout |editor-first=Michael D. C. |editor-link=Michael D. C. Drout |title=Frodo |work=[[J.R.R. Tolkien Encyclopedia|J.R.R. Tolkien Encyclopedia: Scholarship and Critical Assessment]] |year=2013 |origyear=2007 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |isbn=978-0-415-86511-1 |pages=223\u2013225 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{The Lord of the Rings}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baggins, Frodo}}\n[[Category:The Lord of the Rings characters]]\n[[Category:Middle-earth Hobbits]]\n[[Category:Adventure film characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional orphans]]\n[[Category:Bearers of the One Ring]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who can turn invisible]]\n[[Category:Literary characters introduced in 1954]]\n[[Category:Fictional swordsmen]]\n[[Category:Fictional amputees]]\n[[Category:Fictional writers]]\n", "name_user": "Rickray777", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Fellowship of the Ring:\"Aragornleads\" changed to \"Aragorn leads\" (space inserted, or typo correction).", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frodo_Baggins"}
{"title_page": "Adlingfleet", "text_new": "{{Short description|Village in the East Riding of Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                  England\n|coordinates = {{coord|53.679646|-0.723667|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name =            Adlingfleet\n|static_image_name =        Adlingfleet.jpg\n|static_image_caption =     North end of Adlingfleet on a winter day\n|population =               \n|civil_parish =             [[Twin Rivers, East Riding of Yorkshire|Twin Rivers]]\n|unitary_england =          [[East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n|region =                   Yorkshire and the Humber\n|lieutenancy_england =      [[East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Brigg and Goole (UK Parliament constituency)|Brigg and Goole]]\n|post_town =                GOOLE\n|postcode_district =        DN14\n|postcode_area =            DN\n|dial_code =                01724\n|os_grid_reference =        SE844211\n|london_distance_mi =       150<!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n|london_direction =         S\n}}\n[[File:Adlingfleet map.jpg|thumb|Most of the Adlingfleet Drain is in the Twin Rivers Civil Parish.]]\n'''Adlingfleet''' is a village in the [[East Riding of Yorkshire]], England, that forms part of the [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] of [[Twin Rivers, East Riding of Yorkshire|Twin Rivers]]. It is situated approximately {{convert|7|mi|km}} to the east of [[Goole]] town centre.\n\n==Geography==\nAdlingfleet is located on a minor road which runs along the southern bank of the [[River Ouse, Yorkshire|River Ouse]] from [[Swinefleet]] through [[Reedness]], [[Whitgift, East Riding of Yorkshire|Whitgift]] and [[Ousefleet]] before turning to the south by [[Blacktoft Sands RSPB reserve]] to reach the village. The road continues southwards, to [[Fockerby]] and [[Garthorpe, North Lincolnshire|Garthorpe]]. The county boundary between the [[East Riding of Yorkshire]] and [[North Lincolnshire]] forms its southern boundary, which crosses the road just to the south of the village centre, follows the eastern edge of the housing, and turns eastwards to reach the [[River Trent]]. At its north-eastern tip, the boundary cuts across the mud banks, excluding [[Trent Falls]], the point at which the Trent and the Ouse meet, from its jurisdiction.<ref name=osmap>Ordnance Survey, 1:25000 map, 2006</ref>\n\nAll of the surrounding land is low-lying and flat, and is protected from flooding by sea walls along the banks of the Trent to the east and the Ouse to the north. The northern banks are set back from the River Ouse,<ref name=osmap/> creating the largest tidal reedbed in England, which is managed by the [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds]] as a haven for wildlife.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rspb.org.uk/reserves/guide/b/blacktoftsands/about.aspx |title=About Blacktoft Sands |publisher=RSPB |accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> Before the drainage schemes of the 18th&nbsp;century, much more of the area was saltmarsh, and this has resulted in soils with a low [[pH]] and high concentrations of metals, including [[ochre]].<ref>{{harvnb |Nunn |2007 |p=27}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe village was written as \"Adelingesfluet\" in the ''[[Domesday Book]]''. Before the [[Norman conquest of England|Conquest]] the lord of Adlingfleet was [[Siward Barn]]; after, lordship transferred to Geoffrey de la Guerche.<ref>[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/search-results.asp?searchtype=quicksearch&query=adlingfleet&catid=24&pagenumber=1&querytype=1&mediaarray=*  \"Documents Online: Adlingfleet\"],  Folio: 326r, 379v, ''Great Domesday Book'';  [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]]. Retrieved 16 December 2011</ref><ref>{{OpenDomesday|OS=SE8421|name=adlingfleet|display=Adlingfleet|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt was part of the [[Goole Rural District]] in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]] from 1894 to 1974, and was then in the [[Boothferry (district)|Boothferry]] district of [[Humberside]] until 1996.\n\n[[File:All Saints Church Adlingfleet.jpg|thumb|left|All Saints Church, Adlingfleet]]\nThe parish church of All Saints is a [[Grade I listed building]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1083144|desc=Church of All Saints|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> The building has a cruciform plan, with a nave, a chancel, a south aisle, north and south transepts, and a square tower at the west end. Much of it is 13th&nbsp;century, with some re-used 12th-century doors. The aisle and tower were built in the 15th&nbsp;century, and various amendments were made in 1792\u201394, in 1828 and in 1955\u201357. Internally, the building contains a number of monuments, including a very fine knight effigy to a member of the Haldenby family, who died in 1596.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1083144 |desc=Church of All Saints, Twin Rivers |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> {{convert|66|yd|m}} to the south of the church is a raised platform on which stands the remains of a rectory, dating from the mid-13th&nbsp;century. It is grade II* listed, and was constructed of [[ashlar]] and coursed rubble by John le Franceys, who was Adlingfleet's rector and also a king's counsellor. The remains, which have not had a roof since the 1970s, and the platform on which they stand, are a scheduled ancient monument, as there are thought to be the remains of other structures below the surface.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1016933 |desc=Adlingfleet medieval rectory|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> To the west of the platform is the old vicarage, built by Rev. Tyson in 1796. Some modifications were made in 1835\u201337 by Rev Erskine Neal. The original structure is in yellow-brown brick, with the 1835 extension in red brick.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1083152 |desc=The Old Vicarage|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Adlingfleet Drainage==\nAdlingfleet Level is an area of low-lying land covering around {{convert|5000|acre|ha}}, near where the [[River Trent]] joins the [[River Ouse, Yorkshire|River Ouse]]. In 1764, landowners contacted the civil engineer [[John Smeaton]], who drew up proposals for a drainage scheme. This formed the basis for an [[Act of Parliament]], which the landowners obtained in March 1767. The Act authorised Drainage Commissioners to be appointed, and they asked Smeaton's colleague, [[John Grundy, Jr.]], to act as engineer for the project. David Buffery was the resident engineer and Charles Tate the land surveyor. Grundy made few changes to Smeaton's plans. By July, he had drawn the plans and specifications for the sluice which would connect the main drain to the Trent, and work began on it in August. A contract for the excavation of the main drain was awarded to James Pinkerton and John Dyson in October.<ref name=skempton281>{{harvnb |Skempton |2002 |p=281}}</ref> This was the first known civil engineering contract for both men, but they went on to work together on a number of schemes, including the [[Driffield Navigation]] and the [[Laneham|Laneham Drainage]] project, and seem to have acted as management contractors, organising and supplying labour to these schemes.<ref>{{harvnb |Skempton |2002 |pp=200, 526\u2013527}}</ref> By April 1769, all the major elements of the project had been completed, and the project had cost around \u00a37,000. The Commissioners retained Buffery, to ensure that some remaining minor works were completed to a satisfactory standard.<ref name=skempton281/>\n\nOn 13 June 1903 the Commissioners asked J Simmons, an engineer from Doncaster, to estimate the cost of a pumping plant, which would be built at the head of the drain. He produced plans and drawings, liaising with suppliers to obtain costings for the pumps. The engine house would have been {{convert|18.5|by|30|ft|m}} with a boiler house which was {{convert|11|ft|m}} wide. He submitted the scheme to the Commissioners at a meeting in Goole on 30 June, but they decided that it was too costly, and so he produced a revised scheme, which included a {{convert|75|ft|m|adj=on}} chimney at the engine house. The cost was estimated at \u00a31,452, and another meeting at Goole on 15 July asked him to obtain formal tenders for the engine and pump house. However, the scheme was again considered to be too costly, and the Commissioners wrote to Simmons on 29 July to tell him that it had been cancelled. He invoiced them for 2.5 per cent of the estimate cost, plus travelling expenses, which amounted to \u00a337 1s (\u00a337.05).<ref>Doncaster Archive Service, Document DY/SIM/3/2</ref> Following a half-yearly meeting on 10 May 1904, they wrote to say they were willing to pay 10 guineas (\u00a310.50).<ref>Doncaster Archive Service, Document DY/SIM/3/4</ref>\n\n===1927 Upgrade===\n{{Adlingfleet Drain map}}\nAfter periodic flooding in the 1920s, a survey was made, indicating that the fall on the main drain was around 2&nbsp;inches per mile (30&nbsp;mm per km), which was not sufficient for good drainage by gravity. Based on the premise that a pumping scheme had an annual cost for running and maintenance, whereas lowering the cill was essentially a one-time cost, the Commissioners of the Adlingfleet and Whitgift Drainage Board asked for tenders for a new sluice in December 1926. The cill would be {{convert|2.5|ft|m}} lower than the existing one, and the contract was for construction of the sluice and work on the drain itself, to make it wider and deeper. Near the sluice, the channel would be {{convert|75|ft|m}} wide at the top, {{convert|12|ft|m}} wide at the bottom and {{convert|20.5|ft|m}} deep. Decreasing sizes were specified for six sections over its {{convert|4|mi|km|adj=on}} length, with the final section being {{convert|10|ft|m}} wide at the bottom and only {{convert|1.83|ft|m}} deep. Various bridges would need their foundations lowered and other improvements to be made, while Gill's Close bridge was to be dismantled and not replaced.<ref name=simmons>{{harvnb |Simmons |1929}}</ref>\n\nThe previous sluice was {{convert|10|ft|m}} wide, built of masonry, and was in an unstable condition by this time. The new one would be {{convert|16|ft|m}} wide, with wing walls making the entire structure {{convert|61|ft|m}} wide. It would be {{convert|105|ft|m}} long, and the cill would be {{convert|22.5|ft|m}} below the highest tide level. Construction would be of reinforced concrete, and the sluice would be built slightly to the north of the existing one, so that it could be completed without interrupting the discharge from the drain. Eleven quotations were received, and the contract was awarded to H. Arnold and Son of Doncaster on 15 February 1927, whose estimate was for \u00a313,847. Having built the sluice structure, a new channel was excavated by mechanical excavator, to connect it to the existing drain. On the river side, the new channel was dredged by the [[Aire and Calder Navigation]] Company and covered with stone. They had the necessary plant to complete this part of the work. The benefits were expounded by Simmons, the engineers for the work, in an article which appeared in ''The Concrete Way'' in 1929, where he stated that following the work, the water levels in winter were several inches below the normal summer levels.<ref name=simmons/> In August 1932 Simmons produced a specification for sluice doors to be installed at Willowbank bridge,<ref>Doncaster Archive Service, Document DY/SIM/3/16</ref> but they were not installed.\n\n===Current state===\n[[File:Adlingfleet Sluice 2011.jpg|thumb|left|The outlet sluice into the River Trent]]\nA sluice with pumps was eventually built to the north of Cowlane bridge in Adlingfleet.<ref>Ordnance Survey, 1:2500 map, 1969</ref> The control building carries the date 1984 on a large stone built into the walls. Construction of a sewage treatment works next to the sluice was well advanced in 2011. The bridges at Hoggards Lane, Cowlane and Willowbank have been replaced by corrugated steel tubes, backfilled up to the level of the road surface. Mains bridge is still a single arched brick structure, while at the end of the drain, Whinsgate bridge consists of the main brick arch under the A161 road, with arches in both wing walls, which enable tracks to cross Dodds Dyke and Eastoft Drain. The southern track over Eastoft Drain was formerly the course of the Fockerby Branch of the [[Axholme Joint Railway]] until its closure in 1965.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://crowle.org/?p=61 |title=Crowle Railways \u2013 Axholme Joint Railway |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> At the outfall, the pointed gates have gone, replaced by a circular opening through a massed concrete infill, with a flap gate on the outlet side, and a vertical lifting steel gate on the inland side.\n\nResponsibility for the drain changed in 2005, when the Adlingfleet and Whitgift Drainage Commissioners amalgamated with five other [[Internal Drainage Board]]s, to become part of the Isle of Axholme Internal Drainage Board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ioaidb.co.uk/ |title=Welcome |publisher=Isle of Axholme IDB |accessdate=31 May 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004041607/http://www.ioaidb.co.uk/ |archivedate=4 October 2011 }}</ref> It changed again on 1 April 2011, when the new body amalgamated with three more Internal Drainage Boards to become the Isle of Axholme and North Nottinghamshire Water Level Management Board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ada.org.uk/morenews.php?fs=&id=135 |title=Internal Drainage Board amalgamations |publisher=Association of Drainage Authorities |date=April 2011 |accessdate=1 June 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903072127/http://www.ada.org.uk/morenews.php?fs=&id=135 |archivedate=3 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Eels===\nThe presence of barriers across waterways has been identified as one of the factors behind the decline in [[eel]] populations, and following new regulations introduced in 2009, a study was carried out to assess which catchments bordering the [[Humber]] could provide suitable habitat for eels. Those with pumps were eliminated, but eight waterways were identified as possible candidates for the fitting of eel passes to aid eel migration. On Adlingfleet drain, the entrance sluice acted as a barrier, and there was a second barrier at the sluice and pumping station by Cowlane Bridge. Although rectification was deemed to be difficult, the drain was ranked fourth in a list of tributaries that could support the migration of eels and other migratory fish.{{sfn |Nunn |2011}} By May 2011, an innovative fish-flap had been fitted, which does not compromise the flood protection, but allows fish to pass at certain states of the tide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/news/129992.aspx |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120803111202/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/news/129992.aspx |url-status = dead|archive-date=3 August 2012 |title=Release of elvers as barriers come down |publisher=Environment Agency |date=May 2011 |accessdate=31 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book\n  |title=Gazetteer \u2014 A\u2013Z of Towns Villages and Hamlets\n  |year=2006\n  |publisher=East Riding of Yorkshire Council\n  |p=3\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=http://www2.hull.ac.uk/science/biological_sciences/research/hifi/people/andy_nunn.aspx\n  |title=Humber eel management issues: barriers and stocking\n  |first=Andy\n  |last=Nunn\n  |display-authors=etal\n  |publisher=University of Hull International Fisheries Institute\n  |year=2007\n  |ref=harv\n  |access-date=25 May 2012\n  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304051607/http://www2.hull.ac.uk/science/biological_sciences/research/hifi/people/andy_nunn.aspx\n  |archive-date=4 March 2016\n  |url-status = dead\n  |df=dmy-all\n  }}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/273445080_Prioritising_eel-migration_barriers_for_passage_improvements\n  |title=Prioritising eel-migration barriers for passage improvements\n  |first=Andy |last=Nunn |display-authors=etal\n  |publisher=University of Hull International Fisheries Institute\n  |date=November 2011\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal\n  |title=Land Drainage Outfall Sluice, Trent Falls\n  |first=George H. |last=Simmons\n  |journal=The Concrete Way\n  |year=1929\n  |publisher=Copy in Doncaster Archives, ref DY/SIM/3/16\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |first=Sir Alec |last=Skempton\n  |title=A Biographical Dictionary of Civil Engineers in Great Britain and Ireland: Vol 1: 1500 to 1830 \n  |publisher=Thomas Telford \n  |year=2002 \n  |isbn=978-0-7277-2939-2\n  |ref=harv|display-authors=etal}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n===References===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Adlingfleet}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Yorkshire|England|United Kingdom}}\n{{East Yorkshire|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in the East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Land drainage in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Village in the East Riding of Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                  England\n|coordinates = {{coord|53.679646|-0.723667|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name =            Adlingfleet\n|static_image_name =        Adlingfleet.jpg\n|static_image_caption =     North end of Adlingfleet on a winter day\n|population =               \n|civil_parish =             [[Twin Rivers, East Riding of Yorkshire|Twin Rivers]]\n|unitary_england =          [[East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n|region =                   Yorkshire and the Humber\n|lieutenancy_england =      [[East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n|constituency_westminster = [[Brigg and Goole (UK Parliament constituency)|Brigg and Goole]]\n|post_town =                GOOLE\n|postcode_district =        DN14\n|postcode_area =            DN\n|dial_code =                01724\n|os_grid_reference =        SE844211\n|london_distance_mi =       150<!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n|london_direction =         S\n}}\n[[File:Adlingfleet map.jpg|thumb|Most of the Adlingfleet Drain is in the Twin Rivers Civil Parish.]]\n'''Adlingfleet''' is a village in the [[East Riding of Yorkshire]], England, that forms part of the [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] of [[Twin Rivers, East Riding of Yorkshire|Twin Rivers]]. It is situated approximately {{convert|7|mi|km}} to the east of [[Goole]] town centre.\n\n==Geography==\nAdlingfleet is located on a minor road which runs along the southern bank of the [[River Ouse, Yorkshire|River Ouse]] from [[Swinefleet]] through [[Reedness]], [[Whitgift, East Riding of Yorkshire|Whitgift]] and [[Ousefleet]] before turning to the south by [[Blacktoft Sands RSPB reserve]] to reach the village. The road continues southwards, to [[Fockerby]] and [[Garthorpe, North Lincolnshire|Garthorpe]]. The county boundary between the [[East Riding of Yorkshire]] and [[North Lincolnshire]] forms its southern boundary, which crosses the road just to the south of the village centre, follows the eastern edge of the housing, and turns eastwards to reach the [[River Trent]]. At its north-eastern tip, the boundary cuts across the mud banks, excluding [[Trent Falls]], the point at which the Trent and the Ouse meet, from its jurisdiction.<ref name=osmap>Ordnance Survey, 1:25000 map, 2006</ref>\n\nAll of the surrounding land is low-lying and flat, and is protected from flooding by sea walls along the banks of the Trent to the east and the Ouse to the north. The northern banks are set back from the River Ouse,<ref name=osmap/> creating the largest tidal reedbed in England, which is managed by the [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds]] as a haven for wildlife.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rspb.org.uk/reserves/guide/b/blacktoftsands/about.aspx |title=About Blacktoft Sands |publisher=RSPB |accessdate=25 May 2012}}</ref> Before the drainage schemes of the 18th&nbsp;century, much more of the area was saltmarsh, and this has resulted in soils with a low [[pH]] and high concentrations of metals, including [[ochre]].<ref>{{harvnb |Nunn |2007 |p=27}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe village was written as \"Adelingesfluet\" in the ''[[Domesday Book]]''. Before the [[Norman conquest of England|Conquest]] the lord of Adlingfleet was [[Siward Barn]]; after, lordship transferred to Geoffrey de la Guerche.<ref>[http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/documentsonline/search-results.asp?searchtype=quicksearch&query=adlingfleet&catid=24&pagenumber=1&querytype=1&mediaarray=*  \"Documents Online: Adlingfleet\"],  Folio: 326r, 379v, ''Great Domesday Book'';  [[The National Archives (United Kingdom)|The National Archives]]. Retrieved 16 December 2011</ref><ref>{{OpenDomesday|OS=SE8421|name=adlingfleet|display=Adlingfleet|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt was part of the [[Goole Rural District]] in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]] from 1894 to 1974, and was then in the [[Boothferry (district)|Boothferry]] district of [[Humberside]] until 1996.\n\n[[File:All Saints Church Adlingfleet.jpg|thumb|none|All Saints Church, Adlingfleet]]\nThe parish church of All Saints is a [[Grade I listed building]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1083144|desc=Church of All Saints|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> The building has a cruciform plan, with a nave, a chancel, a south aisle, north and south transepts, and a square tower at the west end. Much of it is 13th&nbsp;century, with some re-used 12th-century doors. The aisle and tower were built in the 15th&nbsp;century, and various amendments were made in 1792\u201394, in 1828 and in 1955\u201357. Internally, the building contains a number of monuments, including a very fine knight effigy to a member of the Haldenby family, who died in 1596.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1083144 |desc=Church of All Saints, Twin Rivers |accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> {{convert|66|yd|m}} to the south of the church is a raised platform on which stands the remains of a rectory, dating from the mid-13th&nbsp;century. It is grade II* listed, and was constructed of [[ashlar]] and coursed rubble by John le Franceys, who was Adlingfleet's rector and also a king's counsellor. The remains, which have not had a roof since the 1970s, and the platform on which they stand, are a scheduled ancient monument, as there are thought to be the remains of other structures below the surface.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1016933 |desc=Adlingfleet medieval rectory|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref> To the west of the platform is the old vicarage, built by Rev. Tyson in 1796. Some modifications were made in 1835\u201337 by Rev Erskine Neal. The original structure is in yellow-brown brick, with the 1835 extension in red brick.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1083152 |desc=The Old Vicarage|accessdate=20 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Adlingfleet Drainage==\nAdlingfleet Level is an area of low-lying land covering around {{convert|5000|acre|ha}}, near where the [[River Trent]] joins the [[River Ouse, Yorkshire|River Ouse]]. In 1764, landowners contacted the civil engineer [[John Smeaton]], who drew up proposals for a drainage scheme. This formed the basis for an [[Act of Parliament]], which the landowners obtained in March 1767. The Act authorised Drainage Commissioners to be appointed, and they asked Smeaton's colleague, [[John Grundy, Jr.]], to act as engineer for the project. David Buffery was the resident engineer and Charles Tate the land surveyor. Grundy made few changes to Smeaton's plans. By July, he had drawn the plans and specifications for the sluice which would connect the main drain to the Trent, and work began on it in August. A contract for the excavation of the main drain was awarded to James Pinkerton and John Dyson in October.<ref name=skempton281>{{harvnb |Skempton |2002 |p=281}}</ref> This was the first known civil engineering contract for both men, but they went on to work together on a number of schemes, including the [[Driffield Navigation]] and the [[Laneham|Laneham Drainage]] project, and seem to have acted as management contractors, organising and supplying labour to these schemes.<ref>{{harvnb |Skempton |2002 |pp=200, 526\u2013527}}</ref> By April 1769, all the major elements of the project had been completed, and the project had cost around \u00a37,000. The Commissioners retained Buffery, to ensure that some remaining minor works were completed to a satisfactory standard.<ref name=skempton281/>\n\nOn 13 June 1903 the Commissioners asked J Simmons, an engineer from Doncaster, to estimate the cost of a pumping plant, which would be built at the head of the drain. He produced plans and drawings, liaising with suppliers to obtain costings for the pumps. The engine house would have been {{convert|18.5|by|30|ft|m}} with a boiler house which was {{convert|11|ft|m}} wide. He submitted the scheme to the Commissioners at a meeting in Goole on 30 June, but they decided that it was too costly, and so he produced a revised scheme, which included a {{convert|75|ft|m|adj=on}} chimney at the engine house. The cost was estimated at \u00a31,452, and another meeting at Goole on 15 July asked him to obtain formal tenders for the engine and pump house. However, the scheme was again considered to be too costly, and the Commissioners wrote to Simmons on 29 July to tell him that it had been cancelled. He invoiced them for 2.5 per cent of the estimate cost, plus travelling expenses, which amounted to \u00a337 1s (\u00a337.05).<ref>Doncaster Archive Service, Document DY/SIM/3/2</ref> Following a half-yearly meeting on 10 May 1904, they wrote to say they were willing to pay 10 guineas (\u00a310.50).<ref>Doncaster Archive Service, Document DY/SIM/3/4</ref>\n\n===1927 Upgrade===\n{{Adlingfleet Drain map}}\nAfter periodic flooding in the 1920s, a survey was made, indicating that the fall on the main drain was around 2&nbsp;inches per mile (30&nbsp;mm per km), which was not sufficient for good drainage by gravity. Based on the premise that a pumping scheme had an annual cost for running and maintenance, whereas lowering the cill was essentially a one-time cost, the Commissioners of the Adlingfleet and Whitgift Drainage Board asked for tenders for a new sluice in December 1926. The cill would be {{convert|2.5|ft|m}} lower than the existing one, and the contract was for construction of the sluice and work on the drain itself, to make it wider and deeper. Near the sluice, the channel would be {{convert|75|ft|m}} wide at the top, {{convert|12|ft|m}} wide at the bottom and {{convert|20.5|ft|m}} deep. Decreasing sizes were specified for six sections over its {{convert|4|mi|km|adj=on}} length, with the final section being {{convert|10|ft|m}} wide at the bottom and only {{convert|1.83|ft|m}} deep. Various bridges would need their foundations lowered and other improvements to be made, while Gill's Close bridge was to be dismantled and not replaced.<ref name=simmons>{{harvnb |Simmons |1929}}</ref>\n\nThe previous sluice was {{convert|10|ft|m}} wide, built of masonry, and was in an unstable condition by this time. The new one would be {{convert|16|ft|m}} wide, with wing walls making the entire structure {{convert|61|ft|m}} wide. It would be {{convert|105|ft|m}} long, and the cill would be {{convert|22.5|ft|m}} below the highest tide level. Construction would be of reinforced concrete, and the sluice would be built slightly to the north of the existing one, so that it could be completed without interrupting the discharge from the drain. Eleven quotations were received, and the contract was awarded to H. Arnold and Son of Doncaster on 15 February 1927, whose estimate was for \u00a313,847. Having built the sluice structure, a new channel was excavated by mechanical excavator, to connect it to the existing drain. On the river side, the new channel was dredged by the [[Aire and Calder Navigation]] Company and covered with stone. They had the necessary plant to complete this part of the work. The benefits were expounded by Simmons, the engineers for the work, in an article which appeared in ''The Concrete Way'' in 1929, where he stated that following the work, the water levels in winter were several inches below the normal summer levels.<ref name=simmons/> In August 1932 Simmons produced a specification for sluice doors to be installed at Willowbank bridge,<ref>Doncaster Archive Service, Document DY/SIM/3/16</ref> but they were not installed.\n\n===Current state===\n[[File:Adlingfleet Sluice 2011.jpg|thumb|left|The outlet sluice into the River Trent]]\nA sluice with pumps was eventually built to the north of Cowlane bridge in Adlingfleet.<ref>Ordnance Survey, 1:2500 map, 1969</ref> The control building carries the date 1984 on a large stone built into the walls. Construction of a sewage treatment works next to the sluice was well advanced in 2011. The bridges at Hoggards Lane, Cowlane and Willowbank have been replaced by corrugated steel tubes, backfilled up to the level of the road surface. Mains bridge is still a single arched brick structure, while at the end of the drain, Whinsgate bridge consists of the main brick arch under the A161 road, with arches in both wing walls, which enable tracks to cross Dodds Dyke and Eastoft Drain. The southern track over Eastoft Drain was formerly the course of the Fockerby Branch of the [[Axholme Joint Railway]] until its closure in 1965.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://crowle.org/?p=61 |title=Crowle Railways \u2013 Axholme Joint Railway |accessdate=6 May 2012}}</ref> At the outfall, the pointed gates have gone, replaced by a circular opening through a massed concrete infill, with a flap gate on the outlet side, and a vertical lifting steel gate on the inland side.\n\nResponsibility for the drain changed in 2005, when the Adlingfleet and Whitgift Drainage Commissioners amalgamated with five other [[Internal Drainage Board]]s, to become part of the Isle of Axholme Internal Drainage Board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ioaidb.co.uk/ |title=Welcome |publisher=Isle of Axholme IDB |accessdate=31 May 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111004041607/http://www.ioaidb.co.uk/ |archivedate=4 October 2011 }}</ref> It changed again on 1 April 2011, when the new body amalgamated with three more Internal Drainage Boards to become the Isle of Axholme and North Nottinghamshire Water Level Management Board.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ada.org.uk/morenews.php?fs=&id=135 |title=Internal Drainage Board amalgamations |publisher=Association of Drainage Authorities |date=April 2011 |accessdate=1 June 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903072127/http://www.ada.org.uk/morenews.php?fs=&id=135 |archivedate=3 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Eels===\nThe presence of barriers across waterways has been identified as one of the factors behind the decline in [[eel]] populations, and following new regulations introduced in 2009, a study was carried out to assess which catchments bordering the [[Humber]] could provide suitable habitat for eels. Those with pumps were eliminated, but eight waterways were identified as possible candidates for the fitting of eel passes to aid eel migration. On Adlingfleet drain, the entrance sluice acted as a barrier, and there was a second barrier at the sluice and pumping station by Cowlane Bridge. Although rectification was deemed to be difficult, the drain was ranked fourth in a list of tributaries that could support the migration of eels and other migratory fish.{{sfn |Nunn |2011}} By May 2011, an innovative fish-flap had been fitted, which does not compromise the flood protection, but allows fish to pass at certain states of the tide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/news/129992.aspx |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120803111202/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/news/129992.aspx |url-status = dead|archive-date=3 August 2012 |title=Release of elvers as barriers come down |publisher=Environment Agency |date=May 2011 |accessdate=31 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book\n  |title=Gazetteer \u2014 A\u2013Z of Towns Villages and Hamlets\n  |year=2006\n  |publisher=East Riding of Yorkshire Council\n  |p=3\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=http://www2.hull.ac.uk/science/biological_sciences/research/hifi/people/andy_nunn.aspx\n  |title=Humber eel management issues: barriers and stocking\n  |first=Andy\n  |last=Nunn\n  |display-authors=etal\n  |publisher=University of Hull International Fisheries Institute\n  |year=2007\n  |ref=harv\n  |access-date=25 May 2012\n  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304051607/http://www2.hull.ac.uk/science/biological_sciences/research/hifi/people/andy_nunn.aspx\n  |archive-date=4 March 2016\n  |url-status = dead\n  |df=dmy-all\n  }}\n*{{cite web\n  |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/273445080_Prioritising_eel-migration_barriers_for_passage_improvements\n  |title=Prioritising eel-migration barriers for passage improvements\n  |first=Andy |last=Nunn |display-authors=etal\n  |publisher=University of Hull International Fisheries Institute\n  |date=November 2011\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal\n  |title=Land Drainage Outfall Sluice, Trent Falls\n  |first=George H. |last=Simmons\n  |journal=The Concrete Way\n  |year=1929\n  |publisher=Copy in Doncaster Archives, ref DY/SIM/3/16\n  |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |first=Sir Alec |last=Skempton\n  |title=A Biographical Dictionary of Civil Engineers in Great Britain and Ireland: Vol 1: 1500 to 1830 \n  |publisher=Thomas Telford \n  |year=2002 \n  |isbn=978-0-7277-2939-2\n  |ref=harv|display-authors=etal}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n===References===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Adlingfleet}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Yorkshire|England|United Kingdom}}\n{{East Yorkshire|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in the East Riding of Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Land drainage in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Indoreli", "label": "safe", "comment": "formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adlingfleet"}
{"title_page": "James Moore (Cornish author)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2012}}\n'''James Harry Manson Moore''' (born 16 December 1929 in [[Saltash]], [[Cornwall]], died 11 May 2017 London, [[United Kingdom]]) was a Cornish author.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/01/25/books/in-defense-of-a-guru.html|title=IN DEFENSE OF A GURU|date=25 January 1981|work=The New York Times|page=22|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> He was a fellow of the Royal Asiatic Society and a leading authority on [[G. I. Gurdjieff]].\n\n==Life and career==\nMoore was a leading authority on G. I. Gurdjieff, becoming active in practical and thematic Gurdjieff studies from 1956, after studying with Kenneth Walker and later with [[Henriette H. Lannes]] (\"Madame Lannes\") as his Gurdjieffian teacher and mentor between October 1957 and December 1978. His first major study, ''Gurdjieff and Mansfield'' (1980), examined the lives of Gurdjieff and the short story writer [[Katherine Mansfield]]. Moore's book challenged the persistent belief that Gurdjieff was somehow responsible when Mansfield, who arrived at Gurdjieff's institute in France suffering from terminal tuberculosis, died within a few months while still his guest.\n\nFrom 1981 to 1994, Moore was responsible for gathering and leading new students in the [[Gurdjieff Society]] in [[London]]. He contributed to research for the 363 page ''Gurdjieff: an Annotated Bibliography'' (1985) compiled by J. Walter Driscoll and the Gurdjieff Foundation of California. During this period he was also a pupil of [[Henri Tracol]] and Maurice Desselle.\n\nA confessed admirer of Gurdjieff and active Gurdjieffian for his entire adult life, Moore was the author of the biography ''Gurdjieff: The Anatomy of a Myth'' (1991). It was republished in 1999 with a revised introduction, under the title ''Gurdjieff: A biograph''.\n\nIn 1994, Moore published \"Moveable Feasts: the Gurdjieff Work\" in ''Religion Today'', challenging certain significant innovations in Gurdjieffian theory and practice introduced worldwide by [[Jeanne de Salzmann]], the Gurdjieff Foundation's de facto leader. (See external links for text of this article.) After his departure from the Foundation's Gurdjieff Society in London, Moore led an independent Gurdjieff Studies group.\n\nIn \"Gurdjieffian Confessions\" (2005), Moore briefly sketched his personal life and provided candid and vivid glimpses of his 38 years as a member of The Gurdjieff Society in London, between 1956 and 1994.\n\nIn 2011 Moore published \"Eminent Gurdjieffians: Lord Pentland\"; [[Henry Sinclair, 2nd Baron Pentland|John Pentland]] was Henry John Sinclair, 2nd Baron Pentland (1907\u20131984). Moore's 100 page biography was written in the style of [[Lytton Strachey]]'s compact 1918 classic \"[[Eminent Victorians]]\". John Pentland was a follower of P. D. Ouspensky for more than a decade, then associated with G. I. Gurdjieff in Paris during his last two years, 1948-1949. Lord Pentland was president of the Gurdjieff Foundation of New York between its founding in 1953 and his death in 1984.\n\n==Works (selected)==\n* (1980) ''Gurdjieff and Mansfield''\n* (1991) ''Gurdjieff: The Anatomy of a Myth'', {{ISBN|1-85230-450-2}}\n* (2005) ''Gurdjieffian Confessions: a self remembered''\n* (2011)  ''Eminent Gurdjieffians: Lord Pentland'' {{ISBN|0-9549470-1-0}}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jamesmoore.org.uk/ James Moore's website]\n* [http://www.gurdjieff-bibliography.com/Current/20_link-to-pg23.pdf] Moveable Feasts: the Gurdjieff Work, first published in Religion Today, Vol. IX No. 2, Spring 1994\n* [https://www.gurdjieff.org.uk/ Gurdjieff Studies Group]\n* [https://www.gurdjieff.org.uk/life-and-work Moore's concise encyclopedia article on Gurdjieff]\n* [http://www.ouspensky.org.uk/ Moore's article \"P. D. Ouspensky: an Appreciation\"]\n* [http://www.gurdjieff-bibliography.com/ gurdjieff-bibliography.com contains several articles by James Moore, excerpts from his books and a bibliography of his Gurdjieffian writings]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, James}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:English non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Cornish writers]]\n[[Category:Fourth Way]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Saltash]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Asiatic Society]]\n[[Category:Cornish non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2012}}\n'''James Harry Manson Moore''' (born 16 December 1929 in [[Saltash]], [[Cornwall]], died 11 May 2017 London, [[United Kingdom]]) was a Cornish author.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/01/25/books/in-defense-of-a-guru.html|title=IN DEFENSE OF A GURU|date=25 January 1981|work=The New York Times|page=22|accessdate=5 July 2012}}</ref> He was a fellow of the Royal Asiatic Society and a leading authority on [[G. I. Gurdjieff]].\n\n==Life and career==\nMoore was a leading authority on G. I. Gurdjieff, becoming active in practical and thematic Gurdjieff studies from 1956, after studying with Kenneth Walker and later with [[Henriette H. Lannes]] (\"Madame Lannes\") as his Gurdjieffian teacher and mentor between October 1957 and December 1978. His first major study, ''Gurdjieff and Mansfield'' (1980), examined the lives of Gurdjieff and the short story writer [[Katherine Mansfield]]. Moore's book challenged the persistent belief that Gurdjieff was somehow responsible when Mansfield, who arrived at Gurdjieff's institute in France suffering from terminal tuberculosis, died within a few months while still his guest.\n\nFrom 1981 to 1994, Moore was responsible for gathering and leading new students in the [[Gurdjieff Society]] in [[London]]. He contributed to research for the 363 page ''Gurdjieff: an Annotated Bibliography'' (1985) compiled by J. Walter Driscoll and the Gurdjieff Foundation of California. During this period he was also a pupil of [[Henri Tracol]] and Maurice Desselle.\n\nA confessed admirer of Gurdjieff and active Gurdjieffian for his entire adult life, Moore was the author of the biography ''Gurdjieff: The Anatomy of a Myth'' (1991). It was republished in 1999 with a revised introduction, under the title ''Gurdjieff: A biograph''.\n\nIn 1994, Moore published \"Moveable Feasts: the Gurdjieff Work\" in ''Religion Today'', challenging certain significant innovations in Gurdjieffian theory and practice introduced worldwide by [[Jeanne de Salzmann]], the Gurdjieff Foundation's de facto leader. (See external links for text of this article.) After his departure from the Foundation's Gurdjieff Society in London, Moore led an independent Gurdjieff Studies group.\n\nIn \"Gurdjieffian Confessions\" (2005), Moore briefly sketched his personal life and provided candid and vivid glimpses of his 38 years as a member of The Gurdjieff Society in London, between 1956 and 1994.\n\nIn 2011 Moore published \"Eminent Gurdjieffians: Lord Pentland\"; [[Henry Sinclair, 2nd Baron Pentland|John Pentland]] was Henry John Sinclair, 2nd Baron Pentland (1907\u20131984). Moore's 100 page biography was written in the style of [[Lytton Strachey]]'s compact 1918 classic \"[[Eminent Victorians]]\". John Pentland was a follower of P. D. Ouspensky for more than a decade, then associated with G. I. Gurdjieff in Paris during his last two years, 1948-1949. Lord Pentland was president of the Gurdjieff Foundation of New York between its founding in 1953 and his death in 1984.\n\n==Works (selected)==\n* (1980) ''Gurdjieff and Mansfield''\n* (1991) ''Gurdjieff: The Anatomy of a Myth'', {{ISBN|1-85230-450-2}}\n* (2005) ''Gurdjieffian Confessions: a self remembered''\n* (2011)  ''Eminent Gurdjieffians: Lord Pentland'' {{ISBN|0-9549470-1-0}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.jamesmoore.org.uk/ James Moore's website]\n* [http://www.gurdjieff-bibliography.com/Current/20_link-to-pg23.pdf] Moveable Feasts: the Gurdjieff Work, first published in Religion Today, Vol. IX No. 2, Spring 1994\n* [https://www.gurdjieff.org.uk/ Gurdjieff Studies Group]\n* [https://www.gurdjieff.org.uk/life-and-work Moore's concise encyclopedia article on Gurdjieff]\n* [http://www.ouspensky.org.uk/ Moore's article \"P. D. Ouspensky: an Appreciation\"]\n* [http://www.gurdjieff-bibliography.com/ gurdjieff-bibliography.com contains several articles by James Moore, excerpts from his books and a bibliography of his Gurdjieffian writings]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moore, James}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:English non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Cornish writers]]\n[[Category:Fourth Way]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Saltash]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Asiatic Society]]\n[[Category:Cornish non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English writers]]\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Moore_(Cornish_author)"}
{"title_page": "Muhammad Shafiq", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Muhammad Shafiq {{flagicon|PAK}}\n| native_name = {{lang-ur|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0634\u0641\u06cc\u0642}}\n| native_name_lang = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| office = 3rd [[Asian Handball Federation|Secretary General of Asian Handball Federation]]\n| term_start = 25 October 2013\n| term_end = \n| president = [[Ahmed Al-Fahad Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah]] {{flagicon|KUW}}\n| predecessor = Dr. Roshan Anand {{flagicon|IND}}\n| successor = \n| office1= [[Pakistan Olympic Association|Treasurer of Pakistan Olympic Association]]\n| term_start1= 4 February 2012\n| term_end1= \n| president1= [[Syed Arif Hasan]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Major]] Muhammad Afzal\n| successor1 = \n| office2 = 3rd [[Pakistan Handball Federation|President of Pakistan Handball Federation]]\n| term_start2 = December 2012\n| term_end2 = \n| predecessor2 = Syed Muhammad Abid Qadri\n| successor2 = \n| office3 = 1st & 3rd [[Pakistan Handball Federation|Secretary General of Pakistan Handball Federation]]\n| term_start3 = February 2007\n| term_end3 = December 2012\n| president3 = Syed Muhammad Abid Qadri\n| predecessor3 = Muhammad Faheem\n| successor3 = Khalid Rashid\n| term_start4 = April 1985\n| term_end4 = December 2004\n| president4 = Ahsan Alam\n| predecessor4 = ''Position created''\n| successor4 = Muhammad Faheem\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1953|11|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Faisalabad]], [[Dominion of Pakistan]] (present-day [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], [[Pakistan]])\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality = [[Pakistan]]i\n| party = \n| otherparty = \n| height = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| education = [[M.S.|M. Sc.]] in Health and Physical Education, <br> M. Sc. in Rural Sociology, <br> Sports Specialisation Course (Athletics Coach)\n| alma_mater = [[University of Agriculture, Faisalabad]] <br> [[University of Mainz]] <br> [[Gomal University]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = Sports administrator\n| known_for = \n| salary = \n| net_worth = \n| awards = [[IHF Badge of Merit]] (Gold)\n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| blank1 = Religion\n| data1 = [[Sunni Islam]]\n| footnotes = }}\n'''Muhammad Shafiq''' ({{lang-ur|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0634\u0641\u06cc\u0642}}; born 11 November 1953) is a [[Pakistan]]i sports administrator and former [[track and field]] athlete. He is [[Asian Handball Federation#AHF Secretary Generals|3rd]] and current Secretary General of [[Asian Handball Federation]] (AHF) since 25 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1051840/shafiq-elected-ahf-secretary-general |title=Shafiq elected AHF secretary-general |work=[[Dawn\u00a0(newspaper)|Dawn Newspaper]]'s Website |accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref> He is also holds the position of President in [[Pakistan Handball Federation]] since 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/amp/172686-Shafiq-re-elected-Handball-Federation-president |title=Shafiq re-elected Handball Federation president |work=www.thenews.com.pk |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMuhammad Shafiq was born on 11 November 1953 in [[Faisalabad]], [[Dominion of Pakistan]]. He competed in several editions of the [[National Games of Pakistan]], winning gold medal in 3000m steeplechase in 1976 edition held at [[Karachi]], gold medal in both 1500m and 3000m steeplechase in 1980 edition held at Karachi. He also participate in various international tournaments which includes [[1995 World Masters Athletics Championships|11th]], [[1999 World Masters Athletics Championships|13th]] and [[2001 World Masters Athletics Championships|14th]] edition of [[World Masters Athletics Championships]] where he stood 1st among the Asian athletes in his age category.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1RNbpX4eT6ji4es2QnExTeNyhUeoZP4xh/view?usp=embed_facebook |title=Buffalo 1995.pdf |work=Google Docs |pages=23 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe completed his [[Master of Science]] degree in [[Rural Sociology]] from [[University of Agriculture, Faisalabad]] in 1981 and then his Master of Science degree in Health and Physical Education from [[Gomal University]], [[Dera Ismail Khan]] in 1990. He had also done a Sports Specialization Course (Athletics trainer) from [[University of Mainz|Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz]], [[Germany]] in 1982.\n\nHe is fluent in [[English language|English]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]] and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] and also speaks a little bit of [[German language|German]]. He is married and has one wife and four children, two daughters and two sons.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nHe started working as Assistant Director of Sports at University of Agriculture, Faisalabad in 1985. In 1990, he was promoted to Director of Sports and served in this position till his superannuation in 2013. During his tenure University of Agriculture, Faisalabad won All-Pakistan Inter-Universities Sports Championships All Round Trophy (Men) in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |title=UAF VC Prof. Dr. Iqrar Ahmad Khan addresses the participants of closing ceremony of handball training course at UAF |url=http://uaf.edu.pk/Events_2012/events/121103.html |publisher=www.uaf.edu.pk |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=UAF Sports achievements 2008 to 2016 |url=http://uaf.edu.pk/directorates/sports/Files/Achivements-DS-2008-2016.pdf |publisher=www.uaf.edu.pk |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sports administration==\n===Asian Handball Federation===\nShafiq entered in [[Asian Handball Federation]] (AHF) in 1992, holding the position of member in [[AHF Council#AHF Promotion and Public Relations Commission|AHF Promotion and Public Relations Commission]] (1992 \u2013 1999) and [[AHF Council#AHF Playing Rules and Referees Commission|AHF Playing Rules and Referees Commission]] (1996 \u2013 2000) before being elected to [[AHF Council]] as Chairman of [[AHF Council#AHF Under Development Countries Commission|AHF Under Development Countries Commission]] (2004 \u2013 2009) and then as Chairman of [[AHF Council#AHF Commission of Youth and School Handball|AHF Commission of Youth and School Handball]] (2009 \u2013 2013). On 25 October 2013, he succeeded [[India]]n sports administrator Dr. Roshan Anand and was elected as AHF Secretary General.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shafiq elected AHF secretary-general |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1051840/shafiq-elected-ahf-secretary-general |publisher=www.dawn.com |accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistan Handball Federation===\nShafiq is founder of [[handball]] in Pakistan. He is also the co-founder of [[Pakistan Handball Federation]] (PHF) in April 1985 and was elected as its Secretary General.<ref>{{cite web |title=History of Pakistan Handball |url=http://pakistanhandball.com/about-club |publisher=www.pakistanhandball.com |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> He is the longest serving PHF Secretary General, holding the position for 24 years from 1985 \u2013 2004 and then from 2007 \u2013 2012. Currently, he is PHF President since December 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Handball federation elects office-bearers |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1302924/handball-federation-elects-office-bearers |publisher=www.dawn.com |accessdate= December 18, 2016}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Shafiq re-elected Handball Federation president |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/amp/172686-Shafiq-re-elected-Handball-Federation-president |publisher=www.thenews.com.pk |accessdate= December 18, 2016}}</ref> Under his leadership, the performance of [[Pakistan national handball team]] and [[Pakistan national beach handball team]] are at their best as they won many medals which includes gold medal in 2nd edition of [[Asian Beach Handball Championship]] 2007 held at [[Bandar Abbas]], gold medal in [[Beach handball at the 2008 Asian Beach Games|1st Asian Beach Games 2008]] held at [[Bali]], and gold medals in 2010 and [[Handball at the 2019 South Asian Games \u2013 Men|2019]] editions of the [[Handball at the South Asian Games|South Asian Games]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pakistanhandball.com/achievement/ |title=Achievement |work=www.pakistanhandball.com |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\nShafiq also held various positions in other sports federations which includes Treasurer of [[Pakistan Olympic Association]] since February 2012 to till date.<ref>{{cite web |title=Syed Arif Hasan elected Pakistan Olympic Association President for record fourth term |url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1033681/syed-arif-hasan-elected-pakistan-olympic-association-president-for-record-fourth-term |publisher=www.insidethegames.biz |accessdate=January 25, 2016}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Arif set to be elected unopposed POA president for another term |url=https://www.geo.tv/amp/258101-arif-set-to-be-elected-unopposed-poa-president-for-another-term |publisher=www.geo.tv |accessdate=November 23, 2019}}</ref> He was elected as Vice-President (1991 \u2013 2000; 2009 \u2013 2013) and Secretary General (2000 \u2013 2009) of [[South Asian Handball Federation]]. He is a Member of Working Group of [[Commonwealth Handball Association]] and National Course Director of Pakistan NOC. He is also a member of [[International Track and Field Coaches Association]] since 1985.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shafiq, Muhammad}}\n[[Category: 1953 births]]\n[[Category: Living people]]\n[[Category: Asian Handball Federation]]\n[[Category: Asian handball biography stubs]]\n[[Category: Pakistani sports executives and administrators]]\n[[Category: University of Agriculture, Faisalabad alumni]]\n[[Category: Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz alumni]]\n[[Category: Gomal University alumni]]\n[[Category: Pakistani people]]\n[[Category: People from Faisalabad]]\n[[Category: People from Punjab, Pakistan]]\n\n{{handball-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Muhammad Shafiq {{flagicon|PAK}}\n| native_name = {{lang-ur|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0634\u0641\u06cc\u0642}}\n| native_name_lang = \n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_upright = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| office = 3rd [[Asian Handball Federation|Secretary General of Asian Handball Federation]]\n| term_start = 25 October 2013\n| term_end = \n| president = [[Ahmed Al-Fahad Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah]] {{flagicon|KUW}}\n| predecessor = Dr. Roshan Anand {{flagicon|IND}}\n| successor = \n| office1= [[Pakistan Olympic Association|Treasurer of Pakistan Olympic Association]]\n| term_start1= 4 February 2012\n| term_end1= \n| president1= [[Syed Arif Hasan]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Major]] Muhammad Afzal\n| successor1 = \n| office2 = 3rd [[Pakistan Handball Federation|President of Pakistan Handball Federation]]\n| term_start2 = December 2012\n| term_end2 = \n| predecessor2 = Syed Muhammad Abid Qadri\n| successor2 = \n| office3 = 1st & 3rd [[Pakistan Handball Federation|Secretary General of Pakistan Handball Federation]]\n| term_start3 = February 2007\n| term_end3 = December 2012\n| president3 = Syed Muhammad Abid Qadri\n| predecessor3 = Muhammad Faheem\n| successor3 = Khalid Rashid\n| term_start4 = April 1985\n| term_end4 = December 2004\n| president4 = Ahsan Alam\n| predecessor4 = ''Position created''\n| successor4 = Muhammad Faheem\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1953|11|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Faisalabad]], [[Dominion of Pakistan]] (present-day [[Punjab, Pakistan|Punjab]], [[Pakistan]])\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| nationality = [[Pakistan]]i\n| party = \n| otherparty = \n| height = \n| spouse = \n| children = \n| education = [[M.S.|M. Sc.]] in Health and Physical Education, <br> M. Sc. in Rural Sociology, <br> Sports Specialisation Course (Athletics Coach)\n| alma_mater = [[University of Agriculture, Faisalabad]] <br> [[University of Mainz]] <br> [[Gomal University]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = Sports administrator\n| known_for = \n| salary = \n| net_worth = \n| awards = [[IHF Badge of Merit]] (Gold)\n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| blank1 = Religion\n| data1 = [[Sunni Islam]]\n| footnotes = }}\n'''Muhammad Shafiq''' ({{lang-ur|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0634\u0641\u06cc\u0642}}; born 11 November 1953) is a [[Pakistan]]i sports administrator and former [[track and field]] athlete. He is [[Asian Handball Federation#AHF Secretary Generals|3rd]] and current Secretary General of [[Asian Handball Federation]] (AHF) since 25 October 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1051840/shafiq-elected-ahf-secretary-general |title=Shafiq elected AHF secretary-general |work=[[Dawn\u00a0(newspaper)|Dawn Newspaper]]'s Website |accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref> He is also holds the position of President in [[Pakistan Handball Federation]] since 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/amp/172686-Shafiq-re-elected-Handball-Federation-president |title=Shafiq re-elected Handball Federation president |work=www.thenews.com.pk |accessdate=December 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMuhammad Shafiq was born on 11 November 1953 in [[Faisalabad]], [[Dominion of Pakistan]]. He competed in several editions of the [[National Games of Pakistan]], winning gold medal in 3000m steeplechase in 1976 edition held at [[Karachi]], gold medal in both 1500m and 3000m steeplechase in 1980 edition held at Karachi. He also participate in various international tournaments which includes [[1995 World Masters Athletics Championships|11th]], [[1999 World Masters Athletics Championships|13th]] and [[2001 World Masters Athletics Championships|14th]] edition of [[World Masters Athletics Championships]] where he stood 1st among the Asian athletes in his age category.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/1RNbpX4eT6ji4es2QnExTeNyhUeoZP4xh/view?usp=embed_facebook |title=Buffalo 1995.pdf |work=Google Docs |pages=23 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe completed his [[Master of Science]] degree in [[Rural Sociology]] from [[University of Agriculture, Faisalabad]] in 1981 and then his Master of Science degree in Health and Physical Education from [[Gomal University]], [[Dera Ismail Khan]] in 1990. He had also done a Sports Specialization Course (Athletics trainer) from [[University of Mainz|Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz]], [[Germany]] in 1982.\n\nHe is fluent in [[English language|English]], [[Urdu language|Urdu]] and [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]] and also speaks a little bit of [[German language|German]]. He is married and has one wife and four children, two daughters and two sons.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\nHe started working as Assistant Director of Sports at University of Agriculture, Faisalabad in 1985. In 1990, he was promoted to Director of Sports and served in this position till his superannuation in 2013. During his tenure University of Agriculture, Faisalabad won All-Pakistan Inter-Universities Sports Championships All Round Trophy (Men) in 2005.<ref>{{cite web |title=UAF VC Prof. Dr. Iqrar Ahmad Khan addresses the participants of closing ceremony of handball training course at UAF |url=http://uaf.edu.pk/Events_2012/events/121103.html |publisher=www.uaf.edu.pk |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=UAF Sports achievements 2008 to 2016 |url=http://uaf.edu.pk/directorates/sports/Files/Achivements-DS-2008-2016.pdf |publisher=www.uaf.edu.pk |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Sports administration==\n===Asian Handball Federation===\nShafiq entered in [[Asian Handball Federation]] (AHF) in 1992, holding the position of member in [[AHF Council#AHF Promotion and Public Relations Commission|AHF Promotion and Public Relations Commission]] (1992 \u2013 1999) and [[AHF Council#AHF Playing Rules and Referees Commission|AHF Playing Rules and Referees Commission]] (1996 \u2013 2000) before being elected to [[AHF Council]] as Chairman of [[AHF Council#AHF Under Development Countries Commission|AHF Under Development Countries Commission]] (2004 \u2013 2009) and then as Chairman of [[AHF Council#AHF Commission of Youth and School Handball|AHF Commission of Youth and School Handball]] (2009 \u2013 2013). On 25 October 2013, he succeeded [[India]]n sports administrator Dr. Roshan Anand and was elected as AHF Secretary General.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shafiq elected AHF secretary-general |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1051840/shafiq-elected-ahf-secretary-general |publisher=www.dawn.com |accessdate=October 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Pakistan Handball Federation===\nShafiq is founder of [[handball]] in Pakistan. He is also the co-founder of [[Pakistan Handball Federation]] (PHF) in April 1985 and was elected as its Secretary General.<ref>{{cite web |title=History of Pakistan Handball |url=http://pakistanhandball.com/about-club |publisher=www.pakistanhandball.com |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> He is the longest serving PHF Secretary General, holding the position for 24 years from 1985 \u2013 2004 and then from 2007 \u2013 2012. Currently, he is PHF President since December 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Handball federation elects office-bearers |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1302924/handball-federation-elects-office-bearers |publisher=www.dawn.com |accessdate= December 18, 2016}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Shafiq re-elected Handball Federation president |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/amp/172686-Shafiq-re-elected-Handball-Federation-president |publisher=www.thenews.com.pk |accessdate= December 18, 2016}}</ref> Under his leadership, the performance of [[Pakistan national handball team]] and [[Pakistan national beach handball team]] are at their best as they won many medals which includes gold medal in 2nd edition of [[Asian Beach Handball Championship]] 2007 held at [[Bandar Abbas]], gold medal in [[Beach handball at the 2008 Asian Beach Games|1st Asian Beach Games 2008]] held at [[Bali]], and gold medals in 2010 and [[Handball at the 2019 South Asian Games \u2013 Men|2019]] editions of the [[Handball at the South Asian Games|South Asian Games]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pakistanhandball.com/achievement/ |title=Achievement |work=www.pakistanhandball.com |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Others===\nShafiq also held various positions in other sports federations which includes Treasurer of [[Pakistan Olympic Association]] since February 2012 to till date.<ref>{{cite web |title=Syed Arif Hasan elected Pakistan Olympic Association President for record fourth term |url=https://www.insidethegames.biz/articles/1033681/syed-arif-hasan-elected-pakistan-olympic-association-president-for-record-fourth-term |publisher=www.insidethegames.biz |accessdate=January 25, 2016}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Arif set to be elected unopposed POA president for another term |url=https://www.geo.tv/amp/258101-arif-set-to-be-elected-unopposed-poa-president-for-another-term |publisher=www.geo.tv |accessdate=November 23, 2019}}</ref> He was elected as Vice-President (1991 \u2013 2000; 2009 \u2013 2013) and Secretary General (2000 \u2013 2009) of [[South Asian Handball Federation]]. He is a Member of Working Group of [[Commonwealth Handball Association]] and National Course Director of Pakistan NOC. He is also a member of [[International Track and Field Coaches Association]] since 1985.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shafiq, Muhammad}}\n[[Category: 1953 births]]\n[[Category: Living people]]\n[[Category: Asian Handball Federation]]\n[[Category: Asian handball biography stubs]]\n[[Category: Pakistani sports executives and administrators]]\n[[Category: University of Agriculture, Faisalabad alumni]]\n[[Category:Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz alumni]]\n[[Category: Gomal University alumni]]\n[[Category: Pakistani people]]\n[[Category: People from Faisalabad]]\n[[Category: People from Punjab, Pakistan]]\n", "name_user": "WorldSportsEdit", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muhammad_Shafiq"}
{"title_page": "International Board on Books for Young People", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=July 2017}}\n\nThe '''International Board on Books for Young People''' ('''IBBY''') is a Swiss [[non-profit organization]] committed to bringing books and children together. The headquarters of the IBBY are located in [[Basel]], Switzerland.\n\n==IBBY History==\nIn 1952 [[Jella Lepman]] organized a meeting in [[Munich]], Germany, called ''International Understanding through Children\u2019s Books''. Many authors, publishers, teachers and philosophers of the time attended the meeting and as a result a committee was appointed to create the International Board on Books for Young People \u2013 IBBY.\n\nA year later in 1953, IBBY was registered as a [[non-profit organization]] in [[Z\u00fcrich]], [[Switzerland]]. The founding members included: [[Erich K\u00e4stner]], [[Lisa Tetzner]], [[Astrid Lindgren]], Jo Tenfjord, Fritz Brunner, Bettina H\u00fcrlimann and Richard Bamberger.  IBBY established an international award in 1956 and since then the [[Hans Christian Andersen Award]] has continued to be awarded every two years.\n\nIBBY has six key aims:\n* to promote international understanding through children's books \n* to give children everywhere the opportunity to have access to books with high literary and artistic standards \n* to encourage the publication and distribution of quality children's books, especially in developing countries \n* to provide support and training for those involved with children and children's literature \n* to stimulate research and scholarly works in the field of children's literature\n* to protect and uphold the Rights of the Child according to the [[Convention on the Rights of the Child|UN Convention on the Rights of the Child]]\n\n==IBBY Organization==\nIBBY was founded in Zurich, Switzerland as a non-profit organization in 1953. Today, it is composed of more than seventy [http://www.ibby.org/ibby-worldwide/national-sections/ National Sections] all over the world. It represents countries with well-developed book publishing and literacy programmes, and other countries with only a few dedicated professionals who are doing pioneer work in children's book publishing and promotion.\n\nIBBY's policies and programmes are determined by its Executive Committee: ten people from different countries and a President, elected biennially by the National Sections at a General Assembly during the [http://www.ibby.org/ibby-worldwide/congresses/ IBBY Congresses], held every two years. They work on a voluntary basis. The daily management of IBBY's affairs is conducted from the IBBY Secretariat in Basel, Switzerland.\n\nThe National Sections are organized in many different ways and operate on national, regional and international levels. In countries that do not have a National Section, individual membership in IBBY is possible. The membership of the National Sections include authors and illustrators, publishers and editors, translators, journalists and critics, teachers, university professors and students, librarians and booksellers, social workers and parents. Annual dues from the National Sections are IBBY's only source of regular income. Independent financing is necessary to support IBBY activities.\n\nAs a non-governmental organization with an official status in [[UNESCO]] and [[UNICEF]], IBBY has a policy-making role as an advocate of children's books. IBBY is committed to the principles of the International Convention on the Rights of the Child, ratified by the United Nations in 1990. One of its main proclamations is the right of the child to a general education and to direct access to information. Thanks to IBBY's insistence, the resolution includes an appeal to all nations to promote the production and distribution of children's books.\n\nIBBY also cooperates with many international organizations and children's book institutions around the world and exhibits at the [[Bologna Children's Book Fair|International Children's Book Fair in Bologna]] and other international book fairs.\n\n==IBBY Awards and Activities==\nSince its founding in 1953, IBBY has grown in the number of awards and projects it supports and in their geographical spread. All these awards and projects share the goal of encouraging quality children's literature and upholding the right of every child to become a reader.\n\nThe most prestigious award in the field of children's literature, the [[Hans Christian Andersen Award]] is given biennially to an author and an illustrator whose complete works have made a lasting contribution to children's literature. The [[IBBY-Asahi Reading Promotion Award|IBBY-ASAHI Reading Promotion Award]] is given biennially to a group or institution whose activities are judged to be making a lasting contribution to reading promotion programmes. IBBY also compiles an [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=270 IBBY Honour List], published biennially, of recommended works for children by outstanding writers, illustrators and translators from its National Sections.\n\nEach year, an IBBY National Section sponsors the [[International Children's Book Day]], held in the first week of April, on or around the anniversary of Hans Christian Andersen's birthday, 2 April. The day is celebrated to inspire a love of reading and to call attention to children's books.\n\nAs part of its belief that every child has the right to become reader, IBBY and its sponsors and donors, provide funding for several reading development projects. The [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=794 IBBY-Yamada Fund] supports projects for reading promotion, establishing libraries, teacher, librarian and parent training as well as workshops for writers, illustrators and editors of children's books.\n\nThe [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=852 IBBY Children in Crisis Fund] was established in 2005 to help children affected by natural disasters, civil disorder or war. The Fund seeks donations for projects that replace or create libraries/collections of appropriate children's books and provide bibliography, the therapeutic use of books and storytelling. In the region of Central Asia, the Middle East and North Africa, these activities are funded by the Sharjah/IBBY Fund for Children in Crisis.\n\nIBBY has established several collections of children's books, each with its own emphasis. The largest is the [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=271 IBBY Documentation Centre of Books for Young People with Disabilities], located at the Toronto Public Library, Toronto. Every two years a selection of Outstanding Books for Young People with Disabilities is compiled and catalogued. The [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=1329 Silent Books] collection is a collection of children's books without words, created as a response to the need for books on the Italian island of Lampedusa, the destination for many refugees fleeing North Africa and the Middle East. Together with the IBBY Honour List selection, these collections are available as Exhibitions.\n\nIBBY has also supported the creation of two virtual collections of children's books, Children's Books in Europe, a collection of books in European languages and Books for Africa/Books from Africa highlighting books published in African languages from Africa.\n\nThe [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=737 Jella Lepman Medal], named after the founder of IBBY, was first awarded in 1991 to persons or institutions that have made a significant contribution to children's literature.\n\n[[USBBY]] (IBBY in the USA) produces an annual [[USBBY Outstanding International Books List]] (the OIB List).<ref>USBBY webisite, http://www.usbby.org/list_oibl.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113004725/http://www.usbby.org/list_oibl.html |date=2013-01-13 }} Retrieved 10 February 2018.</ref>\n\n==Bookbird==\n[http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=276 Bookbird: A Journal of International Children's Literature] ({{ISSN|0006-7377}}) is a refereed journal published quarterly by IBBY.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n* [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=about What is IBBY]. IBBY. Retrieved 6 July 2006.\n* [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=273 Hans Christian Andersen Awards] IBBY. Retrieved 30 July 2009.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n* [http://www.ibby.org Official website: www.ibby.org]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Children's literature organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=July 2017}}\n\nThe '''International Board on Books for Young People''' ('''IBBY''') is a Swiss [[non-profit organization]] committed to bringing books and children together. The headquarters of the IBBY are located in [[Basel]], Switzerland.\n\n==IBBY History==\nIn 1952 Jella Lepman organized a meeting in [[Munich]], Germany, called ''International Understanding through Children\u2019s Books''. Many authors, publishers, teachers and philosophers of the time attended the meeting and as a result a committee was appointed to create the International Board on Books for Young People \u2013 IBBY.\n\nA year later in 1953, IBBY was registered as a [[non-profit organization]] in Zurich, Switzerland. The founding members included: [[Erich K\u00e4stner]], Lisa Tetzner, [[Astrid Lindgren]], Jo Tenfjord, Fritz Brunner, Bettina H\u00fcrlimann and Richard Bamberger.  IBBY established an international award in 1956 and since then the [[Hans Christian Andersen Award]] has continued to be awarded every two years.\n\nIBBY has six key aims:\n* to promote international understanding through children's books \n* to give children everywhere the opportunity to have access to books with high literary and artistic standards \n* to encourage the publication and distribution of quality children's books, especially in developing countries \n* to provide support and training for those involved with children and children's literature \n* to stimulate research and scholarly works in the field of children's literature\n* to protect and uphold the Rights of the Child according to the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child\n\n==IBBY Organization==\nIBBY was founded in Zurich, Switzerland as a non-profit organization in 1953. Today, it is composed of more than seventy [http://www.ibby.org/ibby-worldwide/national-sections/ National Sections] all over the world. It represents countries with well-developed book publishing and literacy programmes, and other countries with only a few dedicated professionals who are doing pioneer work in children's book publishing and promotion.\n\nIBBY's policies and programmes are determined by its Executive Committee: ten people from different countries and a President, elected biennially by the National Sections at a General Assembly during the [http://www.ibby.org/ibby-worldwide/congresses/ IBBY Congresses], held every two years. They work on a voluntary basis. The daily management of IBBY's affairs is conducted from the IBBY Secretariat in Basel, Switzerland.\n\nThe National Sections are organized in many different ways and operate on national, regional and international levels. In countries that do not have a National Section, individual membership in IBBY is possible. The membership of the National Sections include authors and illustrators, publishers and editors, translators, journalists and critics, teachers, university professors and students, librarians and booksellers, social workers and parents. Annual dues from the National Sections are IBBY's only source of regular income. Independent financing is necessary to support IBBY activities.\n\nAs a non-governmental organization with an official status in [[UNESCO]] and [[UNICEF]], IBBY has a policy-making role as an advocate of children's books. IBBY is committed to the principles of the International Convention on the Rights of the Child, ratified by the United Nations in 1990. One of its main proclamations is the right of the child to a general education and to direct access to information. Thanks to IBBY's insistence, the resolution includes an appeal to all nations to promote the production and distribution of children's books.\n\nIBBY also cooperates with many international organizations and children's book institutions around the world and exhibits at the [[Bologna Children's Book Fair|International Children's Book Fair in Bologna]] and other international book fairs.\n\n==IBBY Awards and Activities==\nSince its founding in 1953, IBBY has grown in the number of awards and projects it supports and in their geographical spread. All these awards and projects share the goal of encouraging quality children's literature and upholding the right of every child to become a reader.\n\nThe most prestigious award in the field of children's literature, the [[Hans Christian Andersen Award]] is given biennially to an author and an illustrator whose complete works have made a lasting contribution to children's literature. The [[IBBY-Asahi Reading Promotion Award|IBBY-ASAHI Reading Promotion Award]] is given biennially to a group or institution whose activities are judged to be making a lasting contribution to reading promotion programmes. IBBY also compiles an [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=270 IBBY Honour List], published biennially, of recommended works for children by outstanding writers, illustrators and translators from its National Sections.\n\nEach year, an IBBY National Section sponsors the [[International Children's Book Day]], held in the first week of April, on or around the anniversary of Hans Christian Andersen's birthday, 2 April. The day is celebrated to inspire a love of reading and to call attention to children's books.\n\nAs part of its belief that every child has the right to become reader, IBBY and its sponsors and donors, provide funding for several reading development projects. The [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=794 IBBY-Yamada Fund] supports projects for reading promotion, establishing libraries, teacher, librarian and parent training as well as workshops for writers, illustrators and editors of children's books.\n\nThe [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=852 IBBY Children in Crisis Fund] was established in 2005 to help children affected by natural disasters, civil disorder or war. The Fund seeks donations for projects that replace or create libraries/collections of appropriate children's books and provide bibliography, the therapeutic use of books and storytelling. In the region of Central Asia, the Middle East and North Africa, these activities are funded by the Sharjah/IBBY Fund for Children in Crisis.\n\nIBBY has established several collections of children's books, each with its own emphasis. The largest is the [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=271 IBBY Documentation Centre of Books for Young People with Disabilities], located at the Toronto Public Library, Toronto. Every two years a selection of Outstanding Books for Young People with Disabilities is compiled and catalogued. The [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=1329 Silent Books] collection is a collection of children's books without words, created as a response to the need for books on the Italian island of Lampedusa, the destination for many refugees fleeing North Africa and the Middle East. Together with the IBBY Honour List selection, these collections are available as Exhibitions.\n\nIBBY has also supported the creation of two virtual collections of children's books, Children's Books in Europe, a collection of books in European languages and Books for Africa/Books from Africa highlighting books published in African languages from Africa.\n\nThe [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=737 Jella Lepman Medal], named after the founder of IBBY, was first awarded in 1991 to persons or institutions that have made a significant contribution to children's literature.\n\n[[USBBY]] (IBBY in the USA) produces an annual [[USBBY Outstanding International Books List]] (the OIB List).<ref>USBBY webisite, http://www.usbby.org/list_oibl.html {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130113004725/http://www.usbby.org/list_oibl.html |date=2013-01-13 }} Retrieved 10 February 2018.</ref>\n\n==Bookbird==\n[http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=276 Bookbird: A Journal of International Children's Literature] ({{ISSN|0006-7377}}) is a refereed journal published quarterly by IBBY.\n\n==References==\n<references />\n* [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=about What is IBBY]. IBBY. Retrieved 6 July 2006.\n* [http://www.ibby.org/index.php?id=273 Hans Christian Andersen Awards] IBBY. Retrieved 30 July 2009.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n* [http://www.ibby.org Official website: www.ibby.org]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Children's literature organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Baekemm", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIBBY History:five WL", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Board_on_Books_for_Young_People"}
